{"title_page": "Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name                    = Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton\n| logo                    = Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton Logo.png\n| image                   = Main Building at SHS.png\n| alt                     = \n| caption                 = Image of the main building.\n| motto                   = <!-- or | mottoes = -->\n| motto_translation       = \n| address                 = 150 Valparaiso Avenue\n| city                    = [[Atherton, California|Atherton]]\n| state                   = [[California]]\n| zipcode                 = 94027\n| country                 = United States\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|37|26|55|N|122|11|48|W|region:US-CA_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map             = USA San Francisco Bay Area#USA California#USA\n| other_names             = {{Hlist|SHS|Sacred Heart|Sacred Heart, Atherton}}\n| former_name             = <!-- or | former_names = -->\n| type                    = [[Private school]]\n| religious_affiliation   = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| established             = {{Start date and age|1898}}\n| founder                 = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| closed                  = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| oversight               = [[Society of the Sacred Heart]]\n| us_nces_school_id       = {{NCES Private School ID|00073771|school_name=SACRED HEART SCHOOLS ATHERTON|access_date=December 4, 2019|ref_name=NCES}}\n| director                = Richard A. Dioli<ref>{{cite web |title=Overview |url=https://www.shschools.org/about/leadership |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| teaching_staff          = \n| grades                  = PK\u201312\n| gender                  = [[Mixed-sex education|Co-educational]]\n| enrollment              = 1,167 (2017-2018)<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| ratio                   = \n| campus_size             = {{Convert|63|acres|m2}}\n| campus_type             = \n| colors                  = Cardinal, Black, White {{Color box|#C41E3A}}{{Color box|Black}}{{Color box|White}}\n| athletics_conference    = {{Unbulleted list|[[West Catholic Athletic League]]|[[West Bay Athletic League]]|[[Peninsula Athletic League]]}}\n| mascot                  = Gators\n| nickname                = \n| accreditations          = {{Unbulleted list|California Association of Independent Schools<ref name=\"CAIS\">{{cite web |title=Accreditation: Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |url=https://www.caisca.org/page/22413_Search_for_a_School.asp?school=137 |website=California Association of Independent Schools |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>|[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]<ref name=\"WASC-Accrediting Commission for Schools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acswasc.org/directory_search.cfm|title=WASC-Accrediting Commission for Schools|accessdate=June 5, 2009|author=WASC-ACS}}</ref>|[[Western Catholic Educational Association]]<ref name=\"WCEA\">{{cite web |title=Schools Accredited by WCEA 2019-20 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5abc73b79f877085c0a2a384/t/5d2f3a84c7d90000018ee8e4/1563376260678/2019-20+WCEA+Accredited+Schools.pdf |website=Western Catholic Educational Association |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| publication             = \n| newspaper               = \n| yearbook                = \n| affiliation             = <!-- or | affiliations = -->\n| website                 = {{URL|www.shschools.org}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton''' (commonly referred to as '''SHS''', '''Sacred Heart''', or '''Sacred Heart, Atherton''') is a [[Private school|private]], [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]], [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]] school in [[Atherton, California]], United States. It was established in 1898 by the [[Society of the Sacred Heart]] and is governed by an independent board of trustees.\n\nIt is composed of a preschool and kindergarten; a lower school for grades 1 through 5; a middle school for grades 6 through 8; and a [[college-preparatory school]] for grades 9 through 12. It has been open to both Catholic and non-Catholic students since its inception.<ref name=\"Under the Oaks\"/><ref name=\"Morris\">{{cite journal |last1=Orr |first1=John |title=Sister Nancy's extraordinary 90 years |journal=The Mercury News (San Jose) |date=April 26, 2017 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/04/26/sacred-heart-to-celebrate-sister-nancys-extraordinary-90-years/ |accessdate=November 15, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217165618/https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/04/26/sacred-heart-to-celebrate-sister-nancys-extraordinary-90-years/ |archivedate=February 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Niche (company) |Niche]] ranked it for 2020 as the best Catholic, PK-12, co-educational school in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Best Schools in America |url=https://www.niche.com/k12/search/best-schools/?coedStatus=coed&gradeLevel=pk&religion=catholic&type=private |website=Niche |publisher=Niche.com Inc. |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216205631/http://www.niche.com/k12/search/best-schools/?coedStatus=coed&gradeLevel=pk&religion=catholic&type=private |archivedate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Society of the Sacred Heart]] established girls' schools on six continents, reaching [[San Francisco]] in 1887 in the form of the [[Convent of the Sacred Heart High School (California) |Academy of the Sacred Heart]]. The Reverend Superior of that school, Mother O'Meara, anticipated a need for a [[boarding school]] on the [[San Francisco Peninsula|peninsula]] to the south, leading to the establishment of what would become Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton. The initial plot of {{Convert|40|acres|ha}} was purchased by the Society in 1894 for $20,000 from San Francisco [[Patrick William Riordan |Archbishop Riordan]], who had himself purchased orchard land from the [[Faxon Dean Atherton]] estate.<ref name=\"Under the Oaks\">{{cite book |last1=Gullard |first1=Pamela |last2=Lund |first2=Nancy |title=Under the Oaks |date=2009 |publisher=Scottwall Associates |location=San Francisco |isbn=978-0-942087-20-8 |pages=71-73,203|edition=1st}}</ref> Construction began in February 1897 for the initial wing of a planned two-story, quadrangular structure, with the cornerstone of the first wing laid on May 31, 1897.<ref name=\"Home of the Ladies\">{{cite news |title=Home of the Ladies of the Sacred Heart | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29251960/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=June 6, 1897 |page=21 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Establishment: 1898\u20131944 ===\n[[File:Original Main Building.jpg|thumb|left|The main building, before the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake|1906 earthquake]].]]\nIn 1898, construction of the first wing was completed and Academy of the Sacred Heart of Menlo Park{{refn |group=nb |Atherton was carved out of Menlo Park through a separate incorporation in 1923, although Sacred Heart retained a Menlo Park mailing address until 1989.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Menlo and Broadway renew old sports rivalry to raise money for Oakwood |url=https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/read/47296109/winter-2009-sacred-heart-schools |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=Heart of the Matter |issue=Winter 2009 |page=30}}</ref> While \"Academy of the Sacred Heart of Menlo Park\" was the description used in its Articles of Incorporation,<ref>{{cite news |title=Articles of Incorporation |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38993117/articles_of_incorporation/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Record-Union (Sacramento, California) |date=June 20, 1899 |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> until the mid-1970s the school was also variously referred to in the press as \"Sacred Heart Academy,\" \"Sacred Heart Convent,\" \"Convent of the Sacred Heart,\" and \"Sacred Heart Menlo.\"}} opened its doors to 23 girls and young women. A [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]] [[Elementary School|elementary]] [[day school]] was added in 1906. It was known as St. Joseph's{{refn |group=nb |The co-ed elementary school was established in conjunction with two donations of land{{snd}}{{Convert|5|acres|ha}} in 1904<ref>{{cite news |title=Donates Site for a School |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28254922/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=March 27, 1904 |page=26 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and an additional {{Convert|16|acres|ha}} in 1913<ref>{{cite news |title=Valuable Property is Given to Church | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28255724/valuable_property_is_given_to_church/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=March 6, 1913 |page=10 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>{{snd}}by Emilie Donohoe in memory of her late husband, Joseph.<ref name=\"Heritage\" />}} until 2010 when it was renamed the lower school.<ref name=\"New LMS Campus\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Millie |title=Brand new classrooms greet Sacred Heart students at lower and middle campus |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/08/27/brand-new-classrooms-greet-sacred-heart-students-at-lower-and-middle-school-campus/ |website=InMenlo.com |publisher=InMenlo LLC |accessdate=February 13, 2019 |date=August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMaterials were being gathered for the construction of a second building when the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] struck, causing considerable damage. Sister Emily Healy recounted that \"by six the (attic) floor gave way under the fallen chimney, (and) the arcade with its massive columns had been wrenched out of place and thrown against the children's refectory and the assembly room, breaking windows in its fall.\"<ref name=\"Under the Oaks\" /> Sacred Heart students took refuge at St. Joseph's and within two months a $90,000 reconstruction and renovation project was underway, adding a third story, a new chapel, new classrooms and dormitories, parlors, a large [[porte-coch\u00e8re]], and a bell tower.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart is to rebuild |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29251647/the_san_francisco_call/ |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=The San Francisco Call |date=June 8, 1906 |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> In 1913, construction commenced on a second structure, \"a three-story building adjoining the main buildings which (increased) the capacity threefold.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=$100,000 Chapel Proposed - Two Fine Buildings to be Constructed in Menlo Park |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28255844/100000_chapel_proposed_two_fine/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=May 8, 1913 |page=8 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThe school's senior class of 1899 consisted of just one student.<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite book |last1=Morris |first1=Sr. Nancy |title=Heritage with a Future |date=1998}}</ref> In 1944, 13 seniors graduated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pre-Graduation Parties for Menlo Park Students |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29249719/pregraduation_parties_for_menlo_park/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Times (San Mateo) |date=May 31, 1944 |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Expansion: 1945\u20131983 ===\nThe period after [[World War II]] saw steady growth in Sacred Heart's [[physical plant]], much of it on behalf of the lower and middle school grades. New facilities included a swimming pool in 1954; tennis courts in 1956; a rebuilt St. Joseph's school in 1956; a separate girls' elementary school in 1958; the Sigall middle school building in 1961; a multipurpose building for St. Joseph's in 1965; and, a science building for St. Joseph's in 1966. In 1969, the co-educational St. Joseph's and [[Single-sex education|all-girls]] Sacred Heart elementary merged, retaining the St. Joseph's name.<ref name=\"Heritage\" /> Consistent with the [[Baby boom|post-war childbirth surge]], the number of graduating seniors grew to 55 by 1966<ref name=\"1966 Graduation\">{{cite book |title=Together 1966 (yearbook) |date=1966 |publisher=Sacred Heart High School |url=https://www.classmates.com/siteui/yearbooks/89166 |accessdate=December 12, 2019 |via=[[Classmates.com]]}}</ref> and 60 by 1984.<ref name=\"1984 Graduation\">{{cite book |title=Changes (yearbook) |date=1984 |publisher=Sacred Heart High School |url=https://www.classmates.com/siteui/yearbooks/54484 |accessdate=December 12, 2019 |via=[[Classmates.com]]}}</ref> But the number of boarding students had been declining, and dwindling numbers of Society of the Sacred Heart sisters led to a mostly lay teaching staff by the 1970s and the first lay Head of School, Milton Warner, in 1995.<ref name=\"Heritage\" />\n\n=== Transition: 1984\u20131997 ===\n1984 marked the transformation of Sacred Heart's upper school from a [[Finishing school |finishing school]] for girls{{refn|group=nb|In 1971, the San Francisco [[Diocese#Archdiocese |Archdiocese]] described Sacred Heart as \"a private finishing school... where the very rich send their daughters.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lomax |first1=Almena |title=Catholics Deny Drop in Parochial School Rolls |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40981959/catholics_deny_drop_in_parochial_school/ |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=July 5, 1970 |page=13 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>}} into a co-educational prep school. The boarding program ended, and that fall 30 boys entered a re-branded Sacred Heart Preparatory.<ref name=\"Centennial\">{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Turns 100 |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/news/1998_Jun_3.HEART.html |accessdate=February 12, 2019 |work=Palo Alto Online |date=June 3, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Another school tradition falls; boys to be admitted |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28339607/another_school_tradition_falls_boys_to/ | accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The San Francisco Examiner |date=December 16, 1984 |page=20 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]] caused cosmetic damage to the main building and prompted the school to move its remaining functions elsewhere on campus. In 1996, \"after several years of grappling with whether to tear down the building and build a modern one in its place, or try to save it,\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Sacred Heart also will save old hall |journal=Palo Alto Online |date=June 19, 1996 |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/news/1996_Jun_19.SACRED.html |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> Sacred Heart's board of trustees voted to approve a $4.5 million renovation. The renovation was completed in October 1997. That June, 78 seniors graduated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Prep |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/cover/1997_Jun_13.LIST8.html |accessdate=December 22, 2019 |work=Palo Alto Online |date=June 13, 1997}}</ref>\n\n=== Renovation and expansion: 1998\u2013present ===\nA 1997 capital campaign<ref name=\"Heritage\"/> fueled construction over the next ten years: renovation of the 'West Wing' of the main building to hold a [[library]] on two of its floors in 2000;<ref name=Almanac>{{cite news |last1=Mader |first1=Marjorie |title=Family Almanac: What's New at Private School? |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2000/2000_09_20.private.html |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |publisher=Embarcadero Publishing Co. |date=September 20, 2000}}</ref> a [[performing arts center]], including a 350-seat [[Theater (structure)|theatre]] in 2004; an [[Olympic-size swimming pool]];{{refn|group=nb|The first pool of this size in [[San Mateo County, California |San Mateo County]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harris |first1=Merv |title=The long and short of Bells' chances |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40870978/the_long_and_short_of_bells_chances/ |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=November 3, 1998 |page=22 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>}} and the Homer Science Center in 2008, including a 700-seat [[auditorium]]. A third capital campaign was initiated in 2008 to pay for various improvements,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Sacred Heart to rebuild its Lower & Middle Schools |journal=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=April 21, 2011 |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2011/04/21/sacred-heart-to-rebuild-its-lower--middle-schools |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> ultimately raising $101 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eslinger |first1=Bonnie |title=Good as new: Hillview Middle and Sacred Heart Schools ready for students |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/08/24/good-as-new-hillview-middle-and-sacred-heart-schools-ready-for-students/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=August 24, 2012}}</ref> Subsequent building projects included a new lower and middle school complex in 2012, and a new prep school facility in 2019. The St. Joseph's name was dropped in 2010 with all grades presenting themselves as divisions within Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Millie |title=Brand new classrooms greet Sacred Heart students at lower and middle school campus |journal=InMenlo.com |date=August 27, 2012 |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/08/27/brand-new-classrooms-greet-sacred-heart-students-at-lower-and-middle-school-campus/ |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe 2019 graduating class comprised 148 seniors.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Prep awards diplomas to 121st class |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/print/story/2019/06/12/sacred-heart-prep-awards-diplomas-to-121st-class |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nSacred Heart Schools, Atherton, consists of four divisions: a preschool and kindergarten; a lower school for grades 1{{snd}}5; a middle school for grades 6{{snd}}8; and a college preparatory school for grades 9{{snd}}12.<ref name=\"SHP Profile\">{{cite web|url=https://shschools.myschoolapp.com/ftpimages/783/download/download_2023011.pdf|title=2019-2020 Profile|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The combined school is overseen by a director and supported by centralized administrative functions.\n\n'''Sacred Heart Preparatory''' (commonly called '''Sacred Heart Prep''', '''SHP''', or '''Prep''') was an all-girls school with a significant boarding component until 1984, when it adopted the Preparatory name, ended the boarding program, and started admitting boys. For the 2017{{snd}}2018 school year, SHP had an enrollment of 629 students, half of whom were male, 58% Catholic, and 37% students of color.<ref name=\"NCES\" /><ref name=\"What to Expect\">{{cite journal |title=Entering Sacred Heart Preparatory{{snd}}What to Expect |journal=Life at Sacred Heart Preparatory |date=2019}}</ref>\n\nThe elementary school and middle school are collectively known as the '''Lower and Middle School''' (more commonly, '''LMS'''). The LMS is the result of the 1969 merger of the all-girls Sacred Heart elementary and middle school and the co-ed St. Joseph's elementary.<ref name=\"Centennial\" /> As of the 2017{{snd}}2018 school year, the lower school and middle school had respective enrollments of 323 and 215 students. The preschool and kindergarten, which operates as a separate division, had an enrollment of 107.<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n\nSacred Heart Prep and the LMS hold daytime activities in separate complexes on the SHS campus and have separate principals. While LMS students wear [[school uniforms]], SHP students do not.<ref name='\"LMS Handbook\"'>{{cite book |title=Lower and Middle Schools 2019-2020 Student and Parent Handbook |date=2019 |publisher=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton}}</ref>\n\n=== Governance ===\nSacred Heart is an independent{{refn |group=nb |Sacred Heart is accredited by the California Association of Independent Schools, which is an approved accreditor for the [[National Association of Independent Schools |National Association of Independent Schools (NAIS)]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Approved Accreditors for NAIS Membership |url=https://www.nais.org/membership/international-council-advancing-independent-school-accreditation/approved-accreditors-for-nais-membership/ |website=National Association of Independent Schools |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> and adheres to its independence criteria.<ref>{{cite web |title=School Membership |url=https://www.nais.org/membership/school-membership/ |website=National Association of Independent Schools |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>}} [[501(c)3 organization |non-profit]] school that is controlled by an independent board of trustees, most of whom are [[Laity |lay people]].{{refn |group=nb |In 2018, two trustees were [[Society of the Sacred Heart |RSCJ sisters]], out of 29 trustees in total.<ref>{{cite journal |title=2017-18 Board of Trustees |journal=Sacred Heart Magazine |date=Spring 2018 |page=5 |url=https://issuu.com/danasmithrakoczy/docs/380363_sacredheart_150_winter__18 |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>}} The school remains a mission of the [[Society of the Sacred Heart]] which commits members to educate toward its goals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goals and Criteria |url=https://rscj.org/goals-criteria |website=Society of the Sacred Heart - United States and Canada |publisher=Society of the Sacred Heart |accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> Sacred Heart's independence contrasts with most Catholic schools in the U.S. which are owned or operated by a [[Parish |parish]], [[Diocese |diocese]], or [[Diocese#Archdiocese |archdiocese]] ''(see [[Catholic schools in the United States#Operation | Catholic school operations]])''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walch |first1=Timothy |title=Parish School: American Catholic parochial education from colonial times to the present |date=2003 |publisher=National Catholic Educational Association |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n=== Admissions ===\nSacred Heart's natural admissions points are at the beginning of high school, when the grade expands by about 90 students; at the beginning of middle school, when the grade expands by about 30 students; and at preschool and kindergarten.<ref name=\"NCES\" /> The school requires applicants to provide, among other things, scores from standardized tests:  [[Independent School Entrance Examination]] (ISEE) for middle school<ref>{{cite web |title=Admission - Middle School |url=https://www.shschools.org/admission/middle-school |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref> and High School Placement Test (HSPT) for the Prep.<ref>{{cite web |title=Admission - Preparatory |url=https://www.shschools.org/admission/preparatory |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nTo graduate, students must complete four years of English; four years of religious studies; three years of social science; three years of mathematics (or through algebra 2); two years of French, Latin, Mandarin, or Spanish (or through level 3); two years of science; one and a half years of fine arts; one semester of computer science; and, one semester of health & wellness. The school offers 20 [[Honors student#Honors courses |honors sections]] and 28 [[Advanced Placement |AP]] courses. 89% of SHP's 83 faculty hold master's or doctoral degrees.<ref name=\"What to Expect\" />  Supplementing the college preparatory core are some notable electives, including a sustainable agriculture course where students cultivate vegetables and butcher a goat.<ref name=\"Farm Class\">{{cite journal |last1=Orr |first1=John |title=Sacred Heart's Farm to Cafeteria program teaches students how to grow food to feed the world |journal=The Mercury News |date=August 12, 2016 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/07/15/sacred-hearts-farm-to-cafeteria-program-teaches-students-how-to-grow-food-to-help-feed-the-world/ |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nReligious studies, which the school describes as \"ecumenical and interfaith in content and perspective,\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Religious studies: philosophy & goals |url=https://www.shschools.org/academics/preparatory/departments |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> is a core subject from grades 6{{snd}}12. Students and their families have the option to participate in Catholic or Christian rites, traditions, and practices, including [[Christian liturgy |Eucharistic liturgies]], [[Confirmation |confirmation]], [[Christian meditation |meditations]], and Wednesday morning prayers in the chapel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spirituality and Service - School Programs |url=https://www.shschools.org/campus-life/spirituality--service/school-programs |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |publisher=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> Community service overlaps religious studies, including a requirement to complete at least 25 hours of community service in grade 10 and a [[Capstone course |capstone]] service project in grade 12.<ref>{{cite web |title=Service Learning |url=https://www.shschools.org/Academics/Service-Learning |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Extracurricular activities ==\n=== Athletics ===\nThe school's mascot is the Gators. For baseball and football, Sacred Heart competes in the Bay division of the [[Peninsula Athletic League]] (PAL);<ref>{{cite web |title=Pacific Athletic League |url=https://www.smcoe.org/about/peninsula-athletic-league/current-standings.html |website=San Mateo County Office of Education |publisher=San Mateo County Office of Education |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref> for water polo and boys' lacrosse, the [[West Catholic Athletic League]] (WCAL);<ref>{{cite web |title=WCAL League Standings |url=https://www.wcalsports.org/standings.html |website=West Catholic Athletic League |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref> and, for all other sports, the [[West Bay Athletic League]] (WBAL). All three leagues are in the [[CIF Central Coast Section]] (CCS) of California's NorCal region.{{refn |group=nb |Approximately 1400 high schools in California participate in competitive sports, and they ascend through the following hierarchy: league, section, region, state. Leagues are sometimes further divided.}}\n\n==== Boys' sports ====\nThe school fields boys' sports teams in baseball, basketball, cross-country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming & diving, tennis, track & field, volleyball, and water polo.\n\n'''SHP Boys CCS Championships'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| width=115 | Baseball<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Baseball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/i/m/nnt51kwqqg0baq/CCS_Baseball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>|| 2015\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Basketball<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Basketball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/e/d/hzeohoerrrznac/CCS_Boys_Basketball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>|| 1995, 2006, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2014\n|-\n| Cross{{nbsp}}country<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Cross Country History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/k/j/irrrrbbvkw8w56/CCS_Boys_Cross_Country_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}|| 2006\n|-\n| Football<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Football History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/7/3/mw14oyxss20jra/CCS_Football_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2015 CIF State Football Championship Bowl Games |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/tournament/ul4JqHmgEeW-8KA2nzwbTA/football-fall-15/2015-cif-state-football-championship-bowl-games.htm |website=MaxPreps |publisher=CBS Sports Digital |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> || 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, and 2015{{sup|r}}\n|-\n| Soccer<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Soccer History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/o/o/ljoongk8sqzb2v/CCS_Boys_Soccer_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> || 1988, 1991, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2004, 2006, 2013\n|-\n| Tennis<ref name=\"Boys Tennis\">{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Team Tennis History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/2/0/87mwyshgcl4nnr/CCS_Boys_Team_Tennis_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>|| 2005, 2006{{sup|r}}, 2008{{sup|r}}\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Water{{nbsp}}polo<ref>{{cite web |title=Historical Record of CCS Boys Water Polo Championships |url=http://www.cifccs.org/sports/waterpolo/boys_history |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Water Polo Results\">{{cite web |title=Water Polo Brackets and Results |url=http://www.cifccs.org/sports/waterpolo/index |website=CIF-Central Coast Section |accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>|| 2003, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n|}\n\n<small>\n{|\n|-\n| r = regional championship \n|}\n</small>\n\n==== Girls' sports ====\nThe school fields girls' sports teams in basketball, cross-country, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming & diving, tennis, track & field, volleyball, and water polo. In 1994, Sacred Heart became the smallest school to win a California division I girls' basketball championship.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Witherspoon |first1=Wendy |title=The Biggest Little School - Exclusive Sacred Heart Prep (enrollment 288) Is a Division I Power |url=http://latimes.newspapers.com/clip/39853171/biggest_little_school/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=March 15, 1995 |page=136 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n'''SHP Girls CCS Championships'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Basketball<ref name=\"Girls Basketball\">{{cite web |title=CCS Basketball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/o/b/xvnpkbn90xn67d/CCS_Girls_Basketball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NorCal Game Records |url=https://www.cifstate.org/sports/basketball/past_results_records/CIF_Regional_Basketball_Records_through_2018.pdf |website=California Interscholastic Federation |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=State Championship Records |url=https://www.cifstate.org/sports/basketball/past_results_records/CIF_State_Basketball_Records_through_2018.pdf |website=California Interscholastic Federation |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref>|| 1988, 1989, 1992, 1993{{sup|r,s}}, 1994{{sup|r,s}}, 1995{{sup|r,s}}, 1996{{sup|r,s}}, 1997, 1999{{sup|r,s}}, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2016, 2018\n|-\n| Cross{{nbsp}}country<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Girls Cross Country History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/w/3/sjxo3sv59u8hj1/CCS_Girls_Cross_Country_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}|| 2000 \n|-\n| Soccer<ref>{{cite web |title=Historical Record of CCS Girls Soccer Champions Year-by-Year |url=http://www.cifccs.org/sports/soccer/girls_champion_by_year |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2015 CCS Girls Soccer Division III |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/l/e/qix4gjlr9pv8fx/SOCCER-GIRLS_3-15.pdf |website=CIF - Central Coast Section |publisher=CIF - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2019 CCS Girls Soccer Division IV |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/g/f/y1glygyypc6a8p/SOCCER-GIRLS_D4_19.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher= California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> || 2009, 2014, 2015, 2019, 2020\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Volleyball<ref name=\"Girls Volleyball\">{{cite web |title=CCS Girls Volleyball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/b/o/03rpab4m7i2ylc/CCS_Girls_Volleyball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=State Championship Records |url=https://www.cifstate.org/sports/girls_volleyball/past_results_records/2018_VB_Results_History.pdf |website=California Interscholastic Federation |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref> || 1988, 1990, 1991{{sup|r}}, 1992{{sup|r}}, 1993{{sup|r}}, 1994, 1995{{sup|r,s}}, 1996{{sup|r,s}}, 1997, 1998{{sup|r}}, 2009, 2010{{sup|r}}, 2012{{sup|r}}, 2017{{sup|r}}{{refn |group=nb |In 2017, Sacred Heart won the NorCal regional championship but did not win the CCS championship.}}\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Water{{nbsp}}polo<ref name=\"Girls Water Polo\">{{cite web |title=CCS Girls Water Polo History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/6/r/nz7mmz0s9ke2nc/CCS_Girls_Water_Polo_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Water Polo Results\" />|| 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2019\n|}\n<small>\n{|\n|-\n| r = regional championship || {{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}s = state championship\n|}\n</small>\n\n=== Performing arts ===\nThe school's musical theatre group was nominated for the 2019 Rita Moreno California Music Award,<ref>{{cite news |title=Rita Moreno California High School Musical Honors Announces 2019 Nominees |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/san-francisco/article/Rita-Moreno-California-High-School-Musical-Honors-Announces-2019-Nominees-20190429 |accessdate=November 26, 2019 |work=Broadway World |date=April 29, 2019}}</ref> and its Pulse Dance Team won the Hayward, California regional of the 2019 Rainbow National Dance Competition.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hayward, CA 3/29/2019 Results |url=https://rainbowdance.com/results/2019/429 |website=Rainbow National Dance Competition |publisher=Rainbow Dance Competition, Inc. |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125193832/https://rainbowdance.com/results/2019/429 |archivedate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Traditions ===\n==== Valpo Bowl ====\nThe Valpo Bowl is an annual [[American football |football]] game between Sacred Heart and the neighboring [[Menlo School]] that raises money for a local educational charity.<ref>{{cite web |title= 10th annual Valparaiso Bowl to benefit Peninsula Bridge on Nov. 9 |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/11/06/10th-annual-valparaiso-bowl-to-benefit-peninsula-bridge-on-nov-9/ |website=InMenlo |accessdate=15 November 2019 |date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> The first game was held in 2003, three years after Sacred Heart started its boys football program.<ref name=Almanac/> The Valpo Bowl name stems from both schools having a main entrance on Valparaiso Avenue, although the contest itself is usually held at a neutral venue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazeika |first1=Vytas |title=Valpo Bowl under the lights in Atherton for the first time |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/10/31/valpo-bowl-under-the-lights-in-atherton-for-first-time/ |accessdate=November 12, 2019 |work=The Mercury News |date=October 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe schools have won the following years:<ref>{{cite book |title=Valpo Bowl 2016 Program |date=October 14, 2016 |publisher=Peninsula Bridge |page=2 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55afa91ae4b0e1eb64f87ad8/t/58068aa48419c29b91836958/1476823719801/Valpo+Bowl+2016+Program.pdf |accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* '''SHS:''' 2005, 2008, 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2017,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Valpo Bowl turns into thriller |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/11/04/high-school-football-valpo-bowl-turns-into-thriller/ |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=November 4, 2017}}</ref> 2018,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Valpo Bowl XVI: Sacred Heart Prep crushes rival Menlo School |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/11/02/valpo-bowl-xvi-sacred-heart-prep-crushes-rival-menlo-school/ |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> 2019<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Gators rule Valparaiso with football win over Menlo |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2019/11/09/gators-rule-valapariso-with-football-win-over-menlo |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=Palo Alto Online |date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Menlo:''' 2003, 2004, 2006, 2007, 2009, 2011, 2016<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Menlo snaps 4-game skid in Valpo Bowl series |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/11/05/football-menlo-snaps-4-game-skid-in-valpo-bowl-series/ |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=November 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Religious traditions ====\n[[File:Lourdes Grotto at SHS.png|thumb|right|[[Lourdes grotto]] with Main Building in background.]]\nSacred Heart dismisses students the week before [[Easter]] ([[Holy Week]]) for [[spring break]]. Observed [[Calendar of saints |feast days]] are [[Mater Admirabilis]] (October 20); [[Madeleine Sophie Barat |St. Madeleine Sophie Barat]] (May 25); and, [[Rose Philippine Duchesne |St. Rose Philippine Duchesne]] (November 28). On May 1, LMS students adorn the statue of Our Lady of Lourdes in a May Crowning ceremony.<ref name=\"Summer 2016\">{{cite journal |title=Photo caption |journal=Sacred Heart Magazine |issue=Summer 2016 |url=http://issuu.com/sacredheartschoolsatherton/docs/sacred_heart_summer_2016_magazine |accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|3}}\n\n==== Network-wide traditions  ====\nSacred Heart Schools, Atherton inherits some active traditions from the Society of the Sacred Heart.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart Glossary and Traditions |url=https://rscj.org/vocations/explore/glossary |website=Society of the Sacred Heart - United States and Canada |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Many are French, given the origins of the Society, including ''Cong\u00e9'' (an on-campus day where classes have been unexpectedly cancelled); ''Go\u00fbter'' (an occasional snack distributed by [[Society of the Sacred Heart |RSCJ]]); and, ''Coeur de J\u00e9sus, Sauvez le Monde'' (the school song).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coeur de J\u00e9sus |url=https://aash.org/about-aash/sacred-heart-traditions/coeur-de-jesus |website=Associated Alumnae & Alumni of the Sacred Heart |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nSacred Heart sits on a rectangular, {{Convert|63|acre|adj=on}} campus that stretches along Valparaiso Avenue, about one mile northwest of [[Stanford University]]. Taking Valparaiso as the lower boundary, the campus is laid out with the Oakwood retirement community in the center; the preparatory complex in the lower left quadrant; the lower and middle school complex in the upper right quadrant; and athletic facilities in the upper left and lower right quadrants. A small animal farm is just above Oakwood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart Schools - Campus Map |url=https://shschools.myschoolapp.com/ftpimages/783/download/download_1699629.pdf |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Preparatory complex ===\n'''Main Building''' (1898){{snd}}Repaired and restored after the 1906 and 1989 earthquakes, the Main Building houses school-wide administrative offices, classrooms, meeting and reception rooms, a chapel, and two libraries. At the time of its construction, the design was described as \"in the Italian [[Romanesque Revival architecture |Romanesque]] style, the foundations of concrete, the superstructure of red stock brick, with stone and terra-cotta trimmings and a slate roof.\"<ref name=\"Home of the Ladies\"/> After its 1913 reconstruction, it affected \"a monumental [[Second Empire architecture in the United States and Canada |French Second Empire]] design.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dinkelspiel Cerny |first1=Susan |title=An Architectural Guidebook to San Francisco and the Bay Area |date=2007 |publisher=Gibbs Smith |location=Layton, Utah |isbn=978-1-58685-432-4 |page=158 |edition=1st}}</ref> Combined with the adjoining, 350-seat Performing Arts Center, it forms an open courtyard that partially encloses a [[Labyrinth | labyrinth]] and grotto.\n\n[[File:Homer_Science_Building.png|thumb|right|Homer Science Center (right); Campbell Academic & Arts Center (background).]]\n'''William V. Campbell Academic Arts Building''' (2019){{snd}}The {{Convert|79000|sqft|-2|abbr=on}} building houses flex classrooms and meeting rooms; a performing arts wing; an innovation lab; visual arts studios; a TV and radio station; administrative offices; and an outdoor amphitheater.<ref>{{cite web |title=Atherton Academic Arts Building |url=https://www.xlconstruction.com/portfolio/sacred-heart-schools-atherton-new-academic-arts-building/ |website=Portfolio |publisher=XL Construction |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref> It is named after [[William Campbell (business executive) | Bill Campbell]], a [[Silicon Valley]] business executive, college football coach, and Sacred Heart benefactor. \n\n'''Homer Science Center''' (2009){{snd}}The {{Convert|44000|sqft|-2|abbr=on}} building houses science classrooms, a cafeteria, and a 700-seat auditorium. In 2010, it became the first school building in Silicon Valley to achieve a Platinum [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design | LEED]] rating and received a Top 10 Green Project award by the [[American Institute of Architects]]' Committee on the Environment (AIA/COTE).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gonzales |first1=Neil |title=Sacred Heart adds green building |journal=The Mercury News |date=October 1, 2009 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2009/10/01/sacred-heart-adds-green-building/ |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Homer Science & Student Life Center |url=https://www.aiatopten.org/node/114 |website=American Institute of Architects - Top Ten |publisher=American Institute of Architects |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Homer Science & Student Life Center, California |url=https://www.designbuild-network.com/projects/homerscienceandstude/ |website=Design Build Network |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> It is named after [[Michael Homer]], a computer industry executive.\n\n=== LMS complex ===\nThe lower and middle school complex consists of the Bergeron lower school building,{{refn |group=nb |The Bergeron building is named after [[Douglas G. Bergeron |Doug Bergeron]], the founder of an investment company.}} Xie middle school building, Murphy Administration building, Johnson Performing Arts Center with Ravi Assembly Hall, and Stevens library.\n\n'''Stevens Library''' (2012) has a Platinum [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design | LEED]] rating and was the first school building in California to receive a [[Zero-energy building | Net Zero Energy Building]] Certification from the International Living Future Institute.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Nurturing Sustainability |url=https://www.asumag.com/sustainability-initiatives/modeling-sustainability |website=American School and University |publisher=Informa USA, Inc. |date=August 12, 2016 |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> \"All of the library\u2019s systems, including lighting, heating and water use require no net input from outside sources.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart School Campus Renovation & New Library |url=https://bfsla.com/project/sacred-heart-school/ |website=BFS Landscape Architects - Work |publisher=BFS Landscape Architects |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Athletic facilities ===\n[[File:Dunlevie_Aquatic_Center.png|thumb|right|Dunlevie Aquatic Center.]]\nThe campus has seven tennis courts,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart: New tennis center, track |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2003/2003_11_19.shptnns.html |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=November 19, 2003}}</ref> three [[Gym |gymnasiums]], two baseball fields, a football and track stadium, a soccer field, a lacrosse field, and an [[Olympic-size swimming pool]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Water Polo: Sacred Heart boys continue to shine in pool |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2013/10/02/water-polo-sacred-heart-prep-boys-continue-to-shine-in-pool/ |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Gardens and farm ===\nThe campus supports cultivation of both plants and animals.  The animal farm raises goats, rabbits, ducks, and chickens for the production of cheese, eggs, meat and milk,<ref name=\"Farm Class\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gulker |first1=Linda Hubbard |title=Barnyard in Atherton? Yes, hiding in plain sight at Sacred Heart Schools |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/05/17/barnyard-in-atherton-yes-hiding-in-plain-sight-at-sacred-heart-schools/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=InMenlo |agency=InMenlo, LLC |date=May 17, 2012}}</ref> while {{Convert|10000|sqft|-2|abbr=on}} of organic gardens provide vegetables and herbs to Sacred Heart cafeterias, local charities, and an on-campus farmer\u2019s market.{{refn |group=nb |Sacred Heart is the first school to receive approval from the San Mateo County Department of Environmental Health Services to consume and sell produce in this manner.<ref>{{cite news |title=First in Nation to be Awarded with Platinum LEED for Schools Certification |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100303006639/en/Sacred-Heart-Schools-Atherton-Achieves-Highest-Industry |accessdate=November 28, 2019 |work=Business Wire |publisher=Berkshire Hathaway |date=March 3, 2010}}</ref>}} Lower school students harvest up to {{Convert|2000|lbs|kg|abbr=on}} of Picholine olives from 50 [[Heritage tree |heritage]] olive trees that lie along the campus's western, Elena Avenue border, which are then pressed off-campus into oil.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's olive harvest time at Sacred Heart Schools |url=https://inmenlo.com/2018/10/30/its-olive-harvest-time-at-sacred-heart-schools/ |accessdate=November 28, 2019 |work=InMenlo |publisher=InMenlo LLC |date=October 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brundage |first1=Sandy |title=Harvesting Spirit |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2010/12/05/harvesting-spirit |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |publisher=Embarcadero Publishing |date=December 1, 2010 |pages=25-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Oakwood retirement community ===\nOakwood is the largest of two [[Society of the Sacred Heart |RSCJ]] retirement communities in the United States, with 52 RSCJ.  The first building was opened in 1971, with other structures following in 1981, 1992, 1996, and 2003.  The Gatehouse, a related but separate community, opened in 1987 and was rebuilt in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oakwood Retirement Center |url=https://rscj.org/oakwood-retirement-center |website=Society of the Sacred Heart - United States and Canada |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRSCJ are active on campus in tutoring, lecturing, advising, and leading prayers. Most are paired with seniors in the prep school through the Sacred Heart Society club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart Society |url=https://www.shschools.org/campus-life/spirituality--service/sacred-heart-society |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Directors ==\n* Nancy Morris (1971\u20131989)<ref name=\"Morris\" />\n* Margaret (Peggy) Brown (1989\u20131995)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildermuth |first1=John |title=SCHOOL NOTES -- Donation to Nature Center Provided New Animal Skins |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SCHOOL-NOTES-Donation-to-Nature-Center-3019914.php |accessdate=December 18, 2019 |work=SFGate |publisher=Hearst Communications |date=November 24, 1995}}</ref>\n* Milton (Milt) Werner (1995\u20131998)<ref name=\"Heritage\" />\n* Joan McKenna (1998\u20132000)<ref name=\"New Ciancaglini\" />\n* Joseph Ciancaglini (2000\u20132007)<ref name=\"New Ciancaglini\">{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart names new director |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2000/2000_01_12.sacred.html |accessdate=December 1, 2019 |work=The Almanac |date=January 12, 2000}}</ref>\n* Richard (Rich) Dioli (2007\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news |title=Rich Dioli named director of Sacred Heart Schools |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2007/08/02/rich-dioli-named-director-of-sacred-heart-schools |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |work=The Almanac |date=August 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Cara Black (author) |Cara Black]], author<ref>{{cite news |last1=Freeman |first1=Paul |title=Sharing her mysterious captivation with Paris |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/06/09/sharing-her-mysterious-captivation-with-paris/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Sally Brophy]], Broadway and television actress, and college theatre arts professor<ref>{{cite journal|title=She Follows Her Heart|journal=Radio-TV Mirror|date=December 1953|volume=41|issue=1|pages=14\u201315|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Mirror/53/Mirror-1953-Dec.pdf|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Burr-Kirven]], [[National Football League|NFL]] player\n* [[Caroline Clark |Caroline \"KK\" Clark]], water polo player<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leonard |first1=Jake |title=Sacred Heart wants back in pool with hometown rival |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Sacred-Heart-wants-back-in-pool-with-hometown-2538843.php |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=SF Gate |publisher=Hearst Communications |date=September 26, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Kelly Crowley]], Paralympic swimmer and cyclist<ref>{{cite news |last1=Almond |first1=Elliott |title=Bay Area Paralympians: Kelly Crowley |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/07/19/bay-area-parlaympians-kelly-crowley/ |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |publisher=MediaNews Group, Inc. |date=July 19, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Abby Dahlkemper]], soccer player\n* [[Tierna Davidson]], soccer player<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazeika |first1=Vytas |title=From Atherton prep school to Women's World Cup, duo fulfills dreams |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/06/27/dahlkemper-and-davidson-from-atherton-to-womens-world-cup/ |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |publisher=MediaNews Group, Inc. |date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[David Ellison]], film producer<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Prep graduates 102 |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2001/2001_06_20.gradsh.html |accessdate=November 26, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=June 20, 2001}}</ref>\n* [[Megan Ellison]], film producer and entrepreneur<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewrap.com/oscar-nominations-megan-ellison-first-woman-score-2-best-picture-nods-year/ |title=Oscar Nominations: Megan Ellison First Woman to Score 2 Best Picture Nods in Same Year |publisher=TheWrap |date=January 16, 2014 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Patty Hearst]] (middle school), author and actress<ref>{{cite news |last1=Deutsch |first1=Linda |last2=Meyer |first2=Richard E. | last3=Jenning | first3=Steve |title=Patty Hearst - How \"Princess\" Grew Up on Peninsula |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28324662/patty_hearst_how_princess_grew_up/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Times (San Mateo, California) |date=June 8, 1974 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n* [[Drue Kataoka]], visual artist<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kane |first1=Karla |title=Artscene: Portola Valley's Drue Kataoka on the VR revolution |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2017/07/12/local-artist-global-impact |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Leo Koloamatangi]], [[National Football League|NFL]] player\n* [[Milan Kordestani]], entrepreneur\n* [[Hope Portocarrero]], First Lady of Nicaragua<ref>{{cite news |title=Somoza Honored Here in 1939 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28281834/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The San Francisco Examiner |date=September 30, 1956 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n* [[Melissa Pritchard]], short story writer, novelist, essayist, and journalist\n* [[Kameelah Janan Rasheed]], artist and writer<ref>{{cite news |title=Student wins two prestigious distinctions |url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2005/11/21/student-wins-two-prestigious-distinctions/ |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=East Bay Times |date=November 21, 2005}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Schools of the Sacred Heart]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.shschools.org/}}\n\n{{San Mateo County, California Schools|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic elementary schools in California]]\n[[Category:Catholic middle schools in California]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in California]]\n[[Category:Schools in San Mateo County, California]]\n[[Category:High schools in San Mateo County, California]]\n[[Category:Private K-12 schools in California]]\n[[Category:Sacred Heart schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1898]]\n[[Category:1898 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name                    = Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton\n| logo                    = Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton Logo.png\n| image                   = Main Building at SHS.png\n| alt                     = \n| caption                 = Image of the main building.\n| motto                   = <!-- or | mottoes = -->\n| motto_translation       = \n| address                 = 150 Valparaiso Avenue\n| city                    = [[Atherton, California|Atherton]]\n| state                   = [[California]]\n| zipcode                 = 94027\n| country                 = United States\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|37|26|55|N|122|11|48|W|region:US-CA_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map             = USA San Francisco Bay Area#USA California#USA\n| other_names             = {{Hlist|SHS|Sacred Heart|Sacred Heart, Atherton}}\n| former_name             = <!-- or | former_names = -->\n| type                    = [[Private school]]\n| religious_affiliation   = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| established             = {{Start date and age|1898}}\n| founder                 = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| closed                  = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| oversight               = [[Society of the Sacred Heart]]\n| us_nces_school_id       = {{NCES Private School ID|00073771|school_name=SACRED HEART SCHOOLS ATHERTON|access_date=December 4, 2019|ref_name=NCES}}\n| director                = Richard A. Dioli<ref>{{cite web |title=Overview |url=https://www.shschools.org/about/leadership |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| teaching_staff          = \n| grades                  = PK\u201312\n| gender                  = [[Mixed-sex education|Co-educational]]\n| enrollment              = 1,167 (2017-2018)<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| ratio                   = \n| campus_size             = {{Convert|63|acres|m2}}\n| campus_type             = \n| colors                  = Cardinal, Black, White {{Color box|#C41E3A}}{{Color box|Black}}{{Color box|White}}\n| athletics_conference    = {{Unbulleted list|[[West Catholic Athletic League]]|[[West Bay Athletic League]]|[[Peninsula Athletic League]]}}\n| mascot                  = Gators\n| nickname                = \n| accreditations          = {{Unbulleted list|California Association of Independent Schools<ref name=\"CAIS\">{{cite web |title=Accreditation: Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |url=https://www.caisca.org/page/22413_Search_for_a_School.asp?school=137 |website=California Association of Independent Schools |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>|[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]<ref name=\"WASC-Accrediting Commission for Schools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acswasc.org/directory_search.cfm|title=WASC-Accrediting Commission for Schools|accessdate=June 5, 2009|author=WASC-ACS}}</ref>|[[Western Catholic Educational Association]]<ref name=\"WCEA\">{{cite web |title=Schools Accredited by WCEA 2019-20 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5abc73b79f877085c0a2a384/t/5d2f3a84c7d90000018ee8e4/1563376260678/2019-20+WCEA+Accredited+Schools.pdf |website=Western Catholic Educational Association |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| publication             = \n| newspaper               = \n| yearbook                = \n| affiliation             = <!-- or | affiliations = -->\n| website                 = {{URL|www.shschools.org}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton''' (commonly referred to as '''SHS''', '''Sacred Heart''', or '''Sacred Heart, Atherton''') is a [[Private school|private]], [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]], [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]] school in [[Atherton, California]], United States. It was established in 1898 by the [[Society of the Sacred Heart]] and is governed by an independent board of trustees.\n\nIt is composed of a preschool and kindergarten; a lower school for grades 1 through 5; a middle school for grades 6 through 8; and a [[college-preparatory school]] for grades 9 through 12. It has been open to both Catholic and non-Catholic students since its inception.<ref name=\"Under the Oaks\"/><ref name=\"Morris\">{{cite journal |last1=Orr |first1=John |title=Sister Nancy's extraordinary 90 years |journal=The Mercury News (San Jose) |date=April 26, 2017 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/04/26/sacred-heart-to-celebrate-sister-nancys-extraordinary-90-years/ |accessdate=November 15, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217165618/https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/04/26/sacred-heart-to-celebrate-sister-nancys-extraordinary-90-years/ |archivedate=February 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Niche (company) |Niche]] ranked it for 2020 as the best Catholic, PK-12, co-educational school in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Best Schools in America |url=https://www.niche.com/k12/search/best-schools/?coedStatus=coed&gradeLevel=pk&religion=catholic&type=private |website=Niche |publisher=Niche.com Inc. |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216205631/http://www.niche.com/k12/search/best-schools/?coedStatus=coed&gradeLevel=pk&religion=catholic&type=private |archivedate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Society of the Sacred Heart]] established girls' schools on six continents, reaching [[San Francisco]] in 1887 in the form of the [[Convent of the Sacred Heart High School (California) |Academy of the Sacred Heart]]. The Reverend Superior of that school, Mother O'Meara, anticipated a need for a [[boarding school]] on the [[San Francisco Peninsula|peninsula]] to the south, leading to the establishment of what would become Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton. The initial plot of {{Convert|40|acres|ha}} was purchased by the Society in 1894 for $20,000 from San Francisco [[Patrick William Riordan |Archbishop Riordan]], who had himself purchased orchard land from the [[Faxon Dean Atherton]] estate.<ref name=\"Under the Oaks\">{{cite book |last1=Gullard |first1=Pamela |last2=Lund |first2=Nancy |title=Under the Oaks |date=2009 |publisher=Scottwall Associates |location=San Francisco |isbn=978-0-942087-20-8 |pages=71-73,203|edition=1st}}</ref> Construction began in February 1897 for the initial wing of a planned two-story, quadrangular structure, with the cornerstone of the first wing laid on May 31, 1897.<ref name=\"Home of the Ladies\">{{cite news |title=Home of the Ladies of the Sacred Heart | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29251960/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=June 6, 1897 |page=21 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Establishment: 1898\u20131944 ===\n[[File:Original Main Building.jpg|thumb|left|The main building, before the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake|1906 earthquake]].]]\nIn 1898, construction of the first wing was completed and Academy of the Sacred Heart of Menlo Park{{refn |group=nb |Atherton was carved out of Menlo Park through a separate incorporation in 1923, although Sacred Heart retained a Menlo Park mailing address until 1989.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Menlo and Broadway renew old sports rivalry to raise money for Oakwood |url=https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/read/47296109/winter-2009-sacred-heart-schools |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=Heart of the Matter |issue=Winter 2009 |page=30}}</ref> While \"Academy of the Sacred Heart of Menlo Park\" was the description used in its Articles of Incorporation,<ref>{{cite news |title=Articles of Incorporation |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38993117/articles_of_incorporation/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Record-Union (Sacramento, California) |date=June 20, 1899 |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> until the mid-1970s the school was also variously referred to in the press as \"Sacred Heart Academy,\" \"Sacred Heart Convent,\" \"Convent of the Sacred Heart,\" and \"Sacred Heart Menlo.\"}} opened its doors to 23 girls and young women. A [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]] [[Elementary School|elementary]] [[day school]] was added in 1906. It was known as St. Joseph's{{refn |group=nb |The co-ed elementary school was established in conjunction with two donations of land{{snd}}{{Convert|5|acres|ha}} in 1904<ref>{{cite news |title=Donates Site for a School |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28254922/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=March 27, 1904 |page=26 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and an additional {{Convert|16|acres|ha}} in 1913<ref>{{cite news |title=Valuable Property is Given to Church | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28255724/valuable_property_is_given_to_church/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=March 6, 1913 |page=10 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>{{snd}}by Emilie Donohoe in memory of her late husband, Joseph.<ref name=\"Heritage\" />}} until 2010 when it was renamed the lower school.<ref name=\"New LMS Campus\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Millie |title=Brand new classrooms greet Sacred Heart students at lower and middle campus |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/08/27/brand-new-classrooms-greet-sacred-heart-students-at-lower-and-middle-school-campus/ |website=InMenlo.com |publisher=InMenlo LLC |accessdate=February 13, 2019 |date=August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMaterials were being gathered for the construction of a second building when the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] struck, causing considerable damage. Sister Emily Healy recounted that \"by six the (attic) floor gave way under the fallen chimney, (and) the arcade with its massive columns had been wrenched out of place and thrown against the children's refectory and the assembly room, breaking windows in its fall.\"<ref name=\"Under the Oaks\" /> Sacred Heart students took refuge at St. Joseph's and within two months a $90,000 reconstruction and renovation project was underway, adding a third story, a new chapel, new classrooms and dormitories, parlors, a large [[porte-coch\u00e8re]], and a bell tower.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart is to rebuild |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29251647/the_san_francisco_call/ |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=The San Francisco Call |date=June 8, 1906 |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> In 1913, construction commenced on a second structure, \"a three-story building adjoining the main buildings which (increased) the capacity threefold.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=$100,000 Chapel Proposed - Two Fine Buildings to be Constructed in Menlo Park |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28255844/100000_chapel_proposed_two_fine/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=May 8, 1913 |page=8 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThe school's senior class of 1899 consisted of just one student.<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite book |last1=Morris |first1=Sr. Nancy |title=Heritage with a Future |date=1998}}</ref> In 1944, 13 seniors graduated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pre-Graduation Parties for Menlo Park Students |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29249719/pregraduation_parties_for_menlo_park/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Times (San Mateo) |date=May 31, 1944 |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Expansion: 1945\u20131983 ===\nThe period after [[World War II]] saw steady growth in Sacred Heart's [[physical plant]], much of it on behalf of the lower and middle school grades. New facilities included a swimming pool in 1954; tennis courts in 1956; a rebuilt St. Joseph's school in 1956; a separate girls' elementary school in 1958; the Sigall middle school building in 1961; a multipurpose building for St. Joseph's in 1965; and, a science building for St. Joseph's in 1966. In 1969, the co-educational St. Joseph's and [[Single-sex education|all-girls]] Sacred Heart elementary merged, retaining the St. Joseph's name.<ref name=\"Heritage\" /> Consistent with the [[Baby boom|post-war childbirth surge]], the number of graduating seniors grew to 55 by 1966<ref name=\"1966 Graduation\">{{cite book |title=Together 1966 (yearbook) |date=1966 |publisher=Sacred Heart High School |url=https://www.classmates.com/siteui/yearbooks/89166 |accessdate=December 12, 2019 |via=[[Classmates.com]]}}</ref> and 60 by 1984.<ref name=\"1984 Graduation\">{{cite book |title=Changes (yearbook) |date=1984 |publisher=Sacred Heart High School |url=https://www.classmates.com/siteui/yearbooks/54484 |accessdate=December 12, 2019 |via=[[Classmates.com]]}}</ref> But the number of boarding students had been declining, and dwindling numbers of Society of the Sacred Heart sisters led to a mostly lay teaching staff by the 1970s and the first lay Head of School, Milton Warner, in 1995.<ref name=\"Heritage\" />\n\n=== Transition: 1984\u20131997 ===\n1984 marked the transformation of Sacred Heart's upper school from a [[Finishing school |finishing school]] for girls{{refn|group=nb|In 1971, the San Francisco [[Diocese#Archdiocese |Archdiocese]] described Sacred Heart as \"a private finishing school... where the very rich send their daughters.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lomax |first1=Almena |title=Catholics Deny Drop in Parochial School Rolls |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40981959/catholics_deny_drop_in_parochial_school/ |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=July 5, 1970 |page=13 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>}} into a co-educational prep school. The boarding program ended, and that fall 30 boys entered a re-branded Sacred Heart Preparatory.<ref name=\"Centennial\">{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Turns 100 |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/news/1998_Jun_3.HEART.html |accessdate=February 12, 2019 |work=Palo Alto Online |date=June 3, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Another school tradition falls; boys to be admitted |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28339607/another_school_tradition_falls_boys_to/ | accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The San Francisco Examiner |date=December 16, 1984 |page=20 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]] caused cosmetic damage to the main building and prompted the school to move its remaining functions elsewhere on campus. In 1996, \"after several years of grappling with whether to tear down the building and build a modern one in its place, or try to save it,\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Sacred Heart also will save old hall |journal=Palo Alto Online |date=June 19, 1996 |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/news/1996_Jun_19.SACRED.html |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> Sacred Heart's board of trustees voted to approve a $4.5 million renovation. The renovation was completed in October 1997. That June, 78 seniors graduated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Prep |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/cover/1997_Jun_13.LIST8.html |accessdate=December 22, 2019 |work=Palo Alto Online |date=June 13, 1997}}</ref>\n\n=== Renovation and expansion: 1998\u2013present ===\nA 1997 capital campaign<ref name=\"Heritage\"/> fueled construction over the next ten years: renovation of the 'West Wing' of the main building to hold a [[library]] on two of its floors in 2000;<ref name=Almanac>{{cite news |last1=Mader |first1=Marjorie |title=Family Almanac: What's New at Private School? |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2000/2000_09_20.private.html |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |publisher=Embarcadero Publishing Co. |date=September 20, 2000}}</ref> a [[performing arts center]], including a 350-seat [[Theater (structure)|theatre]] in 2004; an [[Olympic-size swimming pool]];{{refn|group=nb|The first pool of this size in [[San Mateo County, California |San Mateo County]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harris |first1=Merv |title=The long and short of Bells' chances |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40870978/the_long_and_short_of_bells_chances/ |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=November 3, 1998 |page=22 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>}} and the Homer Science Center in 2008, including a 700-seat [[auditorium]]. A third capital campaign was initiated in 2008 to pay for various improvements,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Sacred Heart to rebuild its Lower & Middle Schools |journal=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=April 21, 2011 |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2011/04/21/sacred-heart-to-rebuild-its-lower--middle-schools |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> ultimately raising $101 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eslinger |first1=Bonnie |title=Good as new: Hillview Middle and Sacred Heart Schools ready for students |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/08/24/good-as-new-hillview-middle-and-sacred-heart-schools-ready-for-students/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=August 24, 2012}}</ref> Subsequent building projects included a new lower and middle school complex in 2012, and a new prep school facility in 2019. The St. Joseph's name was dropped in 2010 with all grades presenting themselves as divisions within Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Millie |title=Brand new classrooms greet Sacred Heart students at lower and middle school campus |journal=InMenlo.com |date=August 27, 2012 |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/08/27/brand-new-classrooms-greet-sacred-heart-students-at-lower-and-middle-school-campus/ |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe 2019 graduating class comprised 148 seniors.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Prep awards diplomas to 121st class |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/print/story/2019/06/12/sacred-heart-prep-awards-diplomas-to-121st-class |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nSacred Heart Schools, Atherton, consists of four divisions: a preschool and kindergarten; a lower school for grades 1{{snd}}5; a middle school for grades 6{{snd}}8; and a college preparatory school for grades 9{{snd}}12.<ref name=\"SHP Profile\">{{cite web|url=https://shschools.myschoolapp.com/ftpimages/783/download/download_2023011.pdf|title=2019-2020 Profile|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The combined school is overseen by a director and supported by centralized administrative functions.\n\n'''Sacred Heart Preparatory''' (commonly called '''Sacred Heart Prep''', '''SHP''', or '''Prep''') was an all-girls school with a significant boarding component until 1984, when it adopted the Preparatory name, ended the boarding program, and started admitting boys. For the 2017{{snd}}2018 school year, SHP had an enrollment of 629 students, half of whom were male, 58% Catholic, and 37% students of color.<ref name=\"NCES\" /><ref name=\"What to Expect\">{{cite journal |title=Entering Sacred Heart Preparatory{{snd}}What to Expect |journal=Life at Sacred Heart Preparatory |date=2019}}</ref>\n\nThe elementary school and middle school are collectively known as the '''Lower and Middle School''' (more commonly, '''LMS'''). The LMS is the result of the 1969 merger of the all-girls Sacred Heart elementary and middle school and the co-ed St. Joseph's elementary.<ref name=\"Centennial\" /> As of the 2017{{snd}}2018 school year, the lower school and middle school had respective enrollments of 323 and 215 students. The preschool and kindergarten, which operates as a separate division, had an enrollment of 107.<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n\nSacred Heart Prep and the LMS hold daytime activities in separate complexes on the SHS campus and have separate principals. While LMS students wear [[school uniforms]], SHP students do not.<ref name='\"LMS Handbook\"'>{{cite book |title=Lower and Middle Schools 2019-2020 Student and Parent Handbook |date=2019 |publisher=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton}}</ref>\n\n=== Governance ===\nSacred Heart is an independent{{refn |group=nb |Sacred Heart is accredited by the California Association of Independent Schools, which is an approved accreditor for the [[National Association of Independent Schools |National Association of Independent Schools (NAIS)]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Approved Accreditors for NAIS Membership |url=https://www.nais.org/membership/international-council-advancing-independent-school-accreditation/approved-accreditors-for-nais-membership/ |website=National Association of Independent Schools |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> and adheres to its independence criteria.<ref>{{cite web |title=School Membership |url=https://www.nais.org/membership/school-membership/ |website=National Association of Independent Schools |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>}} [[501(c)3 organization |non-profit]] school that is controlled by an independent board of trustees, most of whom are [[Laity |lay people]].{{refn |group=nb |In 2018, two trustees were [[Society of the Sacred Heart |RSCJ sisters]], out of 29 trustees in total.<ref>{{cite journal |title=2017-18 Board of Trustees |journal=Sacred Heart Magazine |date=Spring 2018 |page=5 |url=https://issuu.com/danasmithrakoczy/docs/380363_sacredheart_150_winter__18 |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>}} The school remains a mission of the [[Society of the Sacred Heart]] which commits members to educate toward its goals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goals and Criteria |url=https://rscj.org/goals-criteria |website=Society of the Sacred Heart - United States and Canada |publisher=Society of the Sacred Heart |accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> Sacred Heart's independence contrasts with most Catholic schools in the U.S. which are owned or operated by a [[Parish |parish]], [[Diocese |diocese]], or [[Diocese#Archdiocese |archdiocese]] ''(see [[Catholic schools in the United States#Operation | Catholic school operations]])''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walch |first1=Timothy |title=Parish School: American Catholic parochial education from colonial times to the present |date=2003 |publisher=National Catholic Educational Association |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n=== Admissions ===\nSacred Heart's natural admissions points are at the beginning of high school, when the grade expands by about 95 students; at the beginning of middle school, when the grade expands by about 30 students; and at preschool and kindergarten.<ref name=\"NCES\" /> The school requires applicants to provide, among other things, scores from standardized tests:  [[Independent School Entrance Examination]] (ISEE) for middle school<ref>{{cite web |title=Admission - Middle School |url=https://www.shschools.org/admission/middle-school |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref> and High School Placement Test (HSPT) for the Prep.<ref>{{cite web |title=Admission - Preparatory |url=https://www.shschools.org/admission/preparatory |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nTo graduate, students must complete four years of English; four years of religious studies; three years of social science; three years of mathematics (or through algebra 2); two years of French, Latin, Mandarin, or Spanish (or through level 3); two years of science; one and a half years of fine arts; one semester of computer science; and, one semester of health & wellness. The school offers 20 [[Honors student#Honors courses |honors sections]] and 28 [[Advanced Placement |AP]] courses. 89% of SHP's 83 faculty hold master's or doctoral degrees.<ref name=\"What to Expect\" />  Supplementing the college preparatory core are some notable electives, including a sustainable agriculture course where students cultivate vegetables and butcher a goat.<ref name=\"Farm Class\">{{cite journal |last1=Orr |first1=John |title=Sacred Heart's Farm to Cafeteria program teaches students how to grow food to feed the world |journal=The Mercury News |date=August 12, 2016 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/07/15/sacred-hearts-farm-to-cafeteria-program-teaches-students-how-to-grow-food-to-help-feed-the-world/ |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nReligious studies, which the school describes as \"ecumenical and interfaith in content and perspective,\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Religious studies: philosophy & goals |url=https://www.shschools.org/academics/preparatory/departments |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> is a core subject from grades 6{{snd}}12. Students and their families have the option to participate in Catholic or Christian rites, traditions, and practices, including [[Christian liturgy |Eucharistic liturgies]], [[Confirmation |confirmation]], [[Christian meditation |meditations]], and Wednesday morning prayers in the chapel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spirituality and Service - School Programs |url=https://www.shschools.org/campus-life/spirituality--service/school-programs |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |publisher=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> Community service overlaps religious studies, including a requirement to complete at least 25 hours of community service in grade 10 and a [[Capstone course |capstone]] service project in grade 12.<ref>{{cite web |title=Service Learning |url=https://www.shschools.org/Academics/Service-Learning |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Extracurricular activities ==\n=== Athletics ===\nThe school's mascot is the Gators. For baseball and football, Sacred Heart competes in the Bay division of the [[Peninsula Athletic League]] (PAL);<ref>{{cite web |title=Pacific Athletic League |url=https://www.smcoe.org/about/peninsula-athletic-league/current-standings.html |website=San Mateo County Office of Education |publisher=San Mateo County Office of Education |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref> for water polo and boys' lacrosse, the [[West Catholic Athletic League]] (WCAL);<ref>{{cite web |title=WCAL League Standings |url=https://www.wcalsports.org/standings.html |website=West Catholic Athletic League |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref> and, for all other sports, the [[West Bay Athletic League]] (WBAL). All three leagues are in the [[CIF Central Coast Section]] (CCS) of California's NorCal region.{{refn |group=nb |Approximately 1400 high schools in California participate in competitive sports, and they ascend through the following hierarchy: league, section, region, state. Leagues are sometimes further divided.}}\n\n==== Boys' sports ====\nThe school fields boys' sports teams in baseball, basketball, cross-country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming & diving, tennis, track & field, volleyball, and water polo.\n\n'''SHP Boys CCS Championships'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| width=115 | Baseball<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Baseball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/i/m/nnt51kwqqg0baq/CCS_Baseball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>|| 2015\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Basketball<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Basketball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/e/d/hzeohoerrrznac/CCS_Boys_Basketball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>|| 1995, 2006, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2014\n|-\n| Cross{{nbsp}}country<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Cross Country History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/k/j/irrrrbbvkw8w56/CCS_Boys_Cross_Country_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}|| 2006\n|-\n| Football<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Football History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/7/3/mw14oyxss20jra/CCS_Football_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2015 CIF State Football Championship Bowl Games |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/tournament/ul4JqHmgEeW-8KA2nzwbTA/football-fall-15/2015-cif-state-football-championship-bowl-games.htm |website=MaxPreps |publisher=CBS Sports Digital |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> || 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, and 2015{{sup|r}}\n|-\n| Soccer<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Soccer History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/o/o/ljoongk8sqzb2v/CCS_Boys_Soccer_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> || 1988, 1991, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2004, 2006, 2013\n|-\n| Tennis<ref name=\"Boys Tennis\">{{cite web |title=CCS Boys Team Tennis History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/2/0/87mwyshgcl4nnr/CCS_Boys_Team_Tennis_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>|| 2005, 2006{{sup|r}}, 2008{{sup|r}}\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Water{{nbsp}}polo<ref>{{cite web |title=Historical Record of CCS Boys Water Polo Championships |url=http://www.cifccs.org/sports/waterpolo/boys_history |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Water Polo Results\">{{cite web |title=Water Polo Brackets and Results |url=http://www.cifccs.org/sports/waterpolo/index |website=CIF-Central Coast Section |accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>|| 2003, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n|}\n\n<small>\n{|\n|-\n| r = regional championship \n|}\n</small>\n\n==== Girls' sports ====\nThe school fields girls' sports teams in basketball, cross-country, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming & diving, tennis, track & field, volleyball, and water polo. In 1994, Sacred Heart became the smallest school to win a California division I girls' basketball championship.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Witherspoon |first1=Wendy |title=The Biggest Little School - Exclusive Sacred Heart Prep (enrollment 288) Is a Division I Power |url=http://latimes.newspapers.com/clip/39853171/biggest_little_school/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=March 15, 1995 |page=136 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n'''SHP Girls CCS Championships'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Basketball<ref name=\"Girls Basketball\">{{cite web |title=CCS Basketball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/o/b/xvnpkbn90xn67d/CCS_Girls_Basketball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NorCal Game Records |url=https://www.cifstate.org/sports/basketball/past_results_records/CIF_Regional_Basketball_Records_through_2018.pdf |website=California Interscholastic Federation |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=State Championship Records |url=https://www.cifstate.org/sports/basketball/past_results_records/CIF_State_Basketball_Records_through_2018.pdf |website=California Interscholastic Federation |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref>|| 1988, 1989, 1992, 1993{{sup|r,s}}, 1994{{sup|r,s}}, 1995{{sup|r,s}}, 1996{{sup|r,s}}, 1997, 1999{{sup|r,s}}, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2016, 2018\n|-\n| Cross{{nbsp}}country<ref>{{cite web |title=CCS Girls Cross Country History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/w/3/sjxo3sv59u8hj1/CCS_Girls_Cross_Country_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}|| 2000 \n|-\n| Soccer<ref>{{cite web |title=Historical Record of CCS Girls Soccer Champions Year-by-Year |url=http://www.cifccs.org/sports/soccer/girls_champion_by_year |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2015 CCS Girls Soccer Division III |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/l/e/qix4gjlr9pv8fx/SOCCER-GIRLS_3-15.pdf |website=CIF - Central Coast Section |publisher=CIF - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2019 CCS Girls Soccer Division IV |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/g/f/y1glygyypc6a8p/SOCCER-GIRLS_D4_19.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher= California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> || 2009, 2014, 2015, 2019, 2020\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Volleyball<ref name=\"Girls Volleyball\">{{cite web |title=CCS Girls Volleyball History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/b/o/03rpab4m7i2ylc/CCS_Girls_Volleyball_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=State Championship Records |url=https://www.cifstate.org/sports/girls_volleyball/past_results_records/2018_VB_Results_History.pdf |website=California Interscholastic Federation |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref> || 1988, 1990, 1991{{sup|r}}, 1992{{sup|r}}, 1993{{sup|r}}, 1994, 1995{{sup|r,s}}, 1996{{sup|r,s}}, 1997, 1998{{sup|r}}, 2009, 2010{{sup|r}}, 2012{{sup|r}}, 2017{{sup|r}}{{refn |group=nb |In 2017, Sacred Heart won the NorCal regional championship but did not win the CCS championship.}}\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | Water{{nbsp}}polo<ref name=\"Girls Water Polo\">{{cite web |title=CCS Girls Water Polo History |url=https://d2o2figo6ddd0g.cloudfront.net/6/r/nz7mmz0s9ke2nc/CCS_Girls_Water_Polo_History.pdf |website=CIF Central Coast Section |publisher=California Interscholastic Federation - Central Coast Section |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Water Polo Results\" />|| 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2019\n|}\n<small>\n{|\n|-\n| r = regional championship || {{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}s = state championship\n|}\n</small>\n\n=== Performing arts ===\nThe school's musical theatre group was nominated for the 2019 Rita Moreno California Music Award,<ref>{{cite news |title=Rita Moreno California High School Musical Honors Announces 2019 Nominees |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/san-francisco/article/Rita-Moreno-California-High-School-Musical-Honors-Announces-2019-Nominees-20190429 |accessdate=November 26, 2019 |work=Broadway World |date=April 29, 2019}}</ref> and its Pulse Dance Team won the Hayward, California regional of the 2019 Rainbow National Dance Competition.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hayward, CA 3/29/2019 Results |url=https://rainbowdance.com/results/2019/429 |website=Rainbow National Dance Competition |publisher=Rainbow Dance Competition, Inc. |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125193832/https://rainbowdance.com/results/2019/429 |archivedate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Traditions ===\n==== Valpo Bowl ====\nThe Valpo Bowl is an annual [[American football |football]] game between Sacred Heart and the neighboring [[Menlo School]] that raises money for a local educational charity.<ref>{{cite web |title= 10th annual Valparaiso Bowl to benefit Peninsula Bridge on Nov. 9 |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/11/06/10th-annual-valparaiso-bowl-to-benefit-peninsula-bridge-on-nov-9/ |website=InMenlo |accessdate=15 November 2019 |date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> The first game was held in 2003, three years after Sacred Heart started its boys football program.<ref name=Almanac/> The Valpo Bowl name stems from both schools having a main entrance on Valparaiso Avenue, although the contest itself is usually held at a neutral venue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazeika |first1=Vytas |title=Valpo Bowl under the lights in Atherton for the first time |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/10/31/valpo-bowl-under-the-lights-in-atherton-for-first-time/ |accessdate=November 12, 2019 |work=The Mercury News |date=October 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe schools have won the following years:<ref>{{cite book |title=Valpo Bowl 2016 Program |date=October 14, 2016 |publisher=Peninsula Bridge |page=2 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55afa91ae4b0e1eb64f87ad8/t/58068aa48419c29b91836958/1476823719801/Valpo+Bowl+2016+Program.pdf |accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* '''SHS:''' 2005, 2008, 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2017,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Valpo Bowl turns into thriller |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/11/04/high-school-football-valpo-bowl-turns-into-thriller/ |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=November 4, 2017}}</ref> 2018,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Valpo Bowl XVI: Sacred Heart Prep crushes rival Menlo School |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/11/02/valpo-bowl-xvi-sacred-heart-prep-crushes-rival-menlo-school/ |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> 2019<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Gators rule Valparaiso with football win over Menlo |url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2019/11/09/gators-rule-valapariso-with-football-win-over-menlo |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=Palo Alto Online |date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Menlo:''' 2003, 2004, 2006, 2007, 2009, 2011, 2016<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=John |title=Menlo snaps 4-game skid in Valpo Bowl series |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/11/05/football-menlo-snaps-4-game-skid-in-valpo-bowl-series/ |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=November 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Religious traditions ====\n[[File:Lourdes Grotto at SHS.png|thumb|right|[[Lourdes grotto]] with Main Building in background.]]\nSacred Heart dismisses students the week before [[Easter]] ([[Holy Week]]) for [[spring break]]. Observed [[Calendar of saints |feast days]] are [[Mater Admirabilis]] (October 20); [[Madeleine Sophie Barat |St. Madeleine Sophie Barat]] (May 25); and, [[Rose Philippine Duchesne |St. Rose Philippine Duchesne]] (November 28). On May 1, LMS students adorn the statue of Our Lady of Lourdes in a May Crowning ceremony.<ref name=\"Summer 2016\">{{cite journal |title=Photo caption |journal=Sacred Heart Magazine |issue=Summer 2016 |url=http://issuu.com/sacredheartschoolsatherton/docs/sacred_heart_summer_2016_magazine |accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|3}}\n\n==== Network-wide traditions  ====\nSacred Heart Schools, Atherton inherits some active traditions from the Society of the Sacred Heart.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart Glossary and Traditions |url=https://rscj.org/vocations/explore/glossary |website=Society of the Sacred Heart - United States and Canada |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Many are French, given the origins of the Society, including ''Cong\u00e9'' (an on-campus day where classes have been unexpectedly cancelled); ''Go\u00fbter'' (an occasional snack distributed by [[Society of the Sacred Heart |RSCJ]]); and, ''Coeur de J\u00e9sus, Sauvez le Monde'' (the school song).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coeur de J\u00e9sus |url=https://aash.org/about-aash/sacred-heart-traditions/coeur-de-jesus |website=Associated Alumnae & Alumni of the Sacred Heart |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nSacred Heart sits on a rectangular, {{Convert|63|acre|adj=on}} campus that stretches along Valparaiso Avenue, about one mile northwest of [[Stanford University]]. Taking Valparaiso as the lower boundary, the campus is laid out with the Oakwood retirement community in the center; the preparatory complex in the lower left quadrant; the lower and middle school complex in the upper right quadrant; and athletic facilities in the upper left and lower right quadrants. A small animal farm is just above Oakwood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart Schools - Campus Map |url=https://shschools.myschoolapp.com/ftpimages/783/download/download_1699629.pdf |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Preparatory complex ===\n'''Main Building''' (1898){{snd}}Repaired and restored after the 1906 and 1989 earthquakes, the Main Building houses school-wide administrative offices, classrooms, meeting and reception rooms, a chapel, and two libraries. At the time of its construction, the design was described as \"in the Italian [[Romanesque Revival architecture |Romanesque]] style, the foundations of concrete, the superstructure of red stock brick, with stone and terra-cotta trimmings and a slate roof.\"<ref name=\"Home of the Ladies\"/> After its 1913 reconstruction, it affected \"a monumental [[Second Empire architecture in the United States and Canada |French Second Empire]] design.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dinkelspiel Cerny |first1=Susan |title=An Architectural Guidebook to San Francisco and the Bay Area |date=2007 |publisher=Gibbs Smith |location=Layton, Utah |isbn=978-1-58685-432-4 |page=158 |edition=1st}}</ref> Combined with the adjoining, 350-seat Performing Arts Center, it forms an open courtyard that partially encloses a [[Labyrinth | labyrinth]] and grotto.\n\n[[File:Homer_Science_Building.png|thumb|right|Homer Science Center (right); Campbell Academic & Arts Center (background).]]\n'''William V. Campbell Academic Arts Building''' (2019){{snd}}The {{Convert|79000|sqft|-2|abbr=on}} building houses flex classrooms and meeting rooms; a performing arts wing; an innovation lab; visual arts studios; a TV and radio station; administrative offices; and an outdoor amphitheater.<ref>{{cite web |title=Atherton Academic Arts Building |url=https://www.xlconstruction.com/portfolio/sacred-heart-schools-atherton-new-academic-arts-building/ |website=Portfolio |publisher=XL Construction |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref> It is named after [[William Campbell (business executive) | Bill Campbell]], a [[Silicon Valley]] business executive, college football coach, and Sacred Heart benefactor. \n\n'''Homer Science Center''' (2009){{snd}}The {{Convert|44000|sqft|-2|abbr=on}} building houses science classrooms, a cafeteria, and a 700-seat auditorium. In 2010, it became the first school building in Silicon Valley to achieve a Platinum [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design | LEED]] rating and received a Top 10 Green Project award by the [[American Institute of Architects]]' Committee on the Environment (AIA/COTE).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gonzales |first1=Neil |title=Sacred Heart adds green building |journal=The Mercury News |date=October 1, 2009 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2009/10/01/sacred-heart-adds-green-building/ |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Homer Science & Student Life Center |url=https://www.aiatopten.org/node/114 |website=American Institute of Architects - Top Ten |publisher=American Institute of Architects |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Homer Science & Student Life Center, California |url=https://www.designbuild-network.com/projects/homerscienceandstude/ |website=Design Build Network |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> It is named after [[Michael Homer]], a computer industry executive.\n\n=== LMS complex ===\nThe lower and middle school complex consists of the Bergeron lower school building,{{refn |group=nb |The Bergeron building is named after [[Douglas G. Bergeron |Doug Bergeron]], the founder of an investment company.}} Xie middle school building, Murphy Administration building, Johnson Performing Arts Center with Ravi Assembly Hall, and Stevens library.\n\n'''Stevens Library''' (2012) has a Platinum [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design | LEED]] rating and was the first school building in California to receive a [[Zero-energy building | Net Zero Energy Building]] Certification from the International Living Future Institute.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Nurturing Sustainability |url=https://www.asumag.com/sustainability-initiatives/modeling-sustainability |website=American School and University |publisher=Informa USA, Inc. |date=August 12, 2016 |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> \"All of the library\u2019s systems, including lighting, heating and water use require no net input from outside sources.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart School Campus Renovation & New Library |url=https://bfsla.com/project/sacred-heart-school/ |website=BFS Landscape Architects - Work |publisher=BFS Landscape Architects |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Athletic facilities ===\n[[File:Dunlevie_Aquatic_Center.png|thumb|right|Dunlevie Aquatic Center.]]\nThe campus has seven tennis courts,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart: New tennis center, track |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2003/2003_11_19.shptnns.html |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=November 19, 2003}}</ref> three [[Gym |gymnasiums]], two baseball fields, a football and track stadium, a soccer field, a lacrosse field, and an [[Olympic-size swimming pool]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Water Polo: Sacred Heart boys continue to shine in pool |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2013/10/02/water-polo-sacred-heart-prep-boys-continue-to-shine-in-pool/ |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Gardens and farm ===\nThe campus supports cultivation of both plants and animals.  The animal farm raises goats, rabbits, ducks, and chickens for the production of cheese, eggs, meat and milk,<ref name=\"Farm Class\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gulker |first1=Linda Hubbard |title=Barnyard in Atherton? Yes, hiding in plain sight at Sacred Heart Schools |url=https://inmenlo.com/2012/05/17/barnyard-in-atherton-yes-hiding-in-plain-sight-at-sacred-heart-schools/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=InMenlo |agency=InMenlo, LLC |date=May 17, 2012}}</ref> while {{Convert|10000|sqft|-2|abbr=on}} of organic gardens provide vegetables and herbs to Sacred Heart cafeterias, local charities, and an on-campus farmer\u2019s market.{{refn |group=nb |Sacred Heart is the first school to receive approval from the San Mateo County Department of Environmental Health Services to consume and sell produce in this manner.<ref>{{cite news |title=First in Nation to be Awarded with Platinum LEED for Schools Certification |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100303006639/en/Sacred-Heart-Schools-Atherton-Achieves-Highest-Industry |accessdate=November 28, 2019 |work=Business Wire |publisher=Berkshire Hathaway |date=March 3, 2010}}</ref>}} Lower school students harvest up to {{Convert|2000|lbs|kg|abbr=on}} of Picholine olives from 50 [[Heritage tree |heritage]] olive trees that lie along the campus's western, Elena Avenue border, which are then pressed off-campus into oil.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's olive harvest time at Sacred Heart Schools |url=https://inmenlo.com/2018/10/30/its-olive-harvest-time-at-sacred-heart-schools/ |accessdate=November 28, 2019 |work=InMenlo |publisher=InMenlo LLC |date=October 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brundage |first1=Sandy |title=Harvesting Spirit |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2010/12/05/harvesting-spirit |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |publisher=Embarcadero Publishing |date=December 1, 2010 |pages=25-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Oakwood retirement community ===\nOakwood is the largest of two [[Society of the Sacred Heart |RSCJ]] retirement communities in the United States, with 52 RSCJ.  The first building was opened in 1971, with other structures following in 1981, 1992, 1996, and 2003.  The Gatehouse, a related but separate community, opened in 1987 and was rebuilt in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oakwood Retirement Center |url=https://rscj.org/oakwood-retirement-center |website=Society of the Sacred Heart - United States and Canada |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRSCJ are active on campus in tutoring, lecturing, advising, and leading prayers. Most are paired with seniors in the prep school through the Sacred Heart Society club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sacred Heart Society |url=https://www.shschools.org/campus-life/spirituality--service/sacred-heart-society |website=Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton |accessdate=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Directors ==\n* Nancy Morris (1971\u20131989)<ref name=\"Morris\" />\n* Margaret (Peggy) Brown (1989\u20131995)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildermuth |first1=John |title=SCHOOL NOTES -- Donation to Nature Center Provided New Animal Skins |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SCHOOL-NOTES-Donation-to-Nature-Center-3019914.php |accessdate=December 18, 2019 |work=SFGate |publisher=Hearst Communications |date=November 24, 1995}}</ref>\n* Milton (Milt) Werner (1995\u20131998)<ref name=\"Heritage\" />\n* Joan McKenna (1998\u20132000)<ref name=\"New Ciancaglini\" />\n* Joseph Ciancaglini (2000\u20132007)<ref name=\"New Ciancaglini\">{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart names new director |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2000/2000_01_12.sacred.html |accessdate=December 1, 2019 |work=The Almanac |date=January 12, 2000}}</ref>\n* Richard (Rich) Dioli (2007\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news |title=Rich Dioli named director of Sacred Heart Schools |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2007/08/02/rich-dioli-named-director-of-sacred-heart-schools |accessdate=December 16, 2019 |work=The Almanac |date=August 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Cara Black (author) |Cara Black]], author<ref>{{cite news |last1=Freeman |first1=Paul |title=Sharing her mysterious captivation with Paris |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/06/09/sharing-her-mysterious-captivation-with-paris/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Sally Brophy]], Broadway and television actress, and college theatre arts professor<ref>{{cite journal|title=She Follows Her Heart|journal=Radio-TV Mirror|date=December 1953|volume=41|issue=1|pages=14\u201315|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Mirror/53/Mirror-1953-Dec.pdf|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Burr-Kirven]], [[National Football League|NFL]] player\n* [[Caroline Clark |Caroline \"KK\" Clark]], water polo player<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leonard |first1=Jake |title=Sacred Heart wants back in pool with hometown rival |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Sacred-Heart-wants-back-in-pool-with-hometown-2538843.php |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=SF Gate |publisher=Hearst Communications |date=September 26, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Kelly Crowley]], Paralympic swimmer and cyclist<ref>{{cite news |last1=Almond |first1=Elliott |title=Bay Area Paralympians: Kelly Crowley |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/07/19/bay-area-parlaympians-kelly-crowley/ |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |publisher=MediaNews Group, Inc. |date=July 19, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Abby Dahlkemper]], soccer player\n* [[Tierna Davidson]], soccer player<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazeika |first1=Vytas |title=From Atherton prep school to Women's World Cup, duo fulfills dreams |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/06/27/dahlkemper-and-davidson-from-atherton-to-womens-world-cup/ |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=The Mercury News (San Jose, California) |publisher=MediaNews Group, Inc. |date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[David Ellison]], film producer<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacred Heart Prep graduates 102 |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/morgue/2001/2001_06_20.gradsh.html |accessdate=November 26, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=June 20, 2001}}</ref>\n* [[Megan Ellison]], film producer and entrepreneur<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewrap.com/oscar-nominations-megan-ellison-first-woman-score-2-best-picture-nods-year/ |title=Oscar Nominations: Megan Ellison First Woman to Score 2 Best Picture Nods in Same Year |publisher=TheWrap |date=January 16, 2014 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Patty Hearst]] (middle school), author and actress<ref>{{cite news |last1=Deutsch |first1=Linda |last2=Meyer |first2=Richard E. | last3=Jenning | first3=Steve |title=Patty Hearst - How \"Princess\" Grew Up on Peninsula |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28324662/patty_hearst_how_princess_grew_up/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Times (San Mateo, California) |date=June 8, 1974 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n* [[Drue Kataoka]], visual artist<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kane |first1=Karla |title=Artscene: Portola Valley's Drue Kataoka on the VR revolution |url=https://www.almanacnews.com/news/2017/07/12/local-artist-global-impact |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The Almanac (Menlo Park, Atherton, Portola Valley, Woodside) |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Leo Koloamatangi]], [[National Football League|NFL]] player\n* [[Milan Kordestani]], entrepreneur\n* [[Hope Portocarrero]], First Lady of Nicaragua<ref>{{cite news |title=Somoza Honored Here in 1939 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28281834/ |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |work=The San Francisco Examiner |date=September 30, 1956 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n* [[Melissa Pritchard]], short story writer, novelist, essayist, and journalist\n* [[Kameelah Janan Rasheed]], artist and writer<ref>{{cite news |title=Student wins two prestigious distinctions |url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2005/11/21/student-wins-two-prestigious-distinctions/ |accessdate=December 21, 2019 |work=East Bay Times |date=November 21, 2005}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Schools of the Sacred Heart]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Sacred Heart Schools, Atherton}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.shschools.org/}}\n\n{{San Mateo County, California Schools|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic elementary schools in California]]\n[[Category:Catholic middle schools in California]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in California]]\n[[Category:Schools in San Mateo County, California]]\n[[Category:High schools in San Mateo County, California]]\n[[Category:Private K-12 schools in California]]\n[[Category:Sacred Heart schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1898]]\n[[Category:1898 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Ottoump", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdmissions:undue specificity; \"about 95\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacred_Heart_Schools,_Atherton"}
{"title_page": "Institute of Food Technologists", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox company \n|name       = Institute of Food Technologists\n|logo       = IFT logo as of 5.24.2010.PNG\n|logo_size  = 150px\n|type       = Non-profit\n|foundation = 1939\n|location   = Chicago, Illinois\n|homepage   = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Institute of Food Technologists''' (IFT) is an international, non-profit scientific society of professionals engaged in food science, food technology, and related areas in academia, government and industry. It has more than 17,000 members from more than 95 countries.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\nAs food technology grew from the individual family farm to the factory level, including the [[slaughterhouse]] for meat and poultry processing, the [[cannery]] for canned foods, and bakeries for bread, the need to have personnel trained for the food industry did also. Literature such as [[Upton Sinclair]]'s ''[[The Jungle]]'' in 1906 about slaughterhouse operations would be a factor in the establishment of the [[Food and Drug Administration (United States)|U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) later that year. The [[United States Department of Agriculture]] was also interested in food technology, and research was already being done at agricultural colleges in the United States, including the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]], the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]], and the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>Goldblith, S.A. (1993). ''Pioneers in Food Science, Volume 1: Samuel Cate Prescott \u2013 M.I.T. Dean and Pioneer Food Technologist.'' Trumball, Connecticut: Food & Nutrition Press, Inc. pp. 99\u2013100.</ref> By 1935, two MIT professors, [[Samuel C. Prescott]] and [[Bernard E. Proctor]] decided that it was time to hold an international conference regarding this.<ref name=\"Goldblith p101\">Goldblith. p. 101.</ref> A detailed proposal was presented to MIT President [[Karl Taylor Compton]] in 1936 was presented with $1500 of financial aid from MIT for a meeting to be held from June 30 to July 2, 1937 with Compton asking how many people would be in attendance at this meeting. Prescott replied with \"fifty or sixty people.\" 500 people actually attended the event.<ref name=\"Goldblith p101\"/>\n\nThis meeting proved so successful that in early 1938 that a second conference would be held in 1939. Initially led by [[George J. Hucker]] of the [[New York State Agricultural Experiment Station]] (part of [[Cornell University]]) in [[Geneva, New York]], a small group meeting was held on August 5, 1938 on forming an organization with an expanded group meeting in New York City on January 16, 1939 to further discuss this.<ref name=\"Goldblith p102\">Goldblith. p. 102.</ref> The second conference was held at MIT June 29 to July 1, 1939 with Proctor as conference chair. 600 people attended this event. At the final session, the chairman of the session [[Fred C. Blanck]] of the United States Department of Agriculture, proposed that an organization be established as the '''Institute of Food Technologists.''' This was approved unanimously. Its first officers were Prescott as President, [[Roy C. Newton]] of [[Swift & Company]] in Chicago, Illinois as Vice President, and Hucker as Secretary-Treasurer.<ref name=\"Goldblith p102\"/> By 1949, IFT had 3,000 members.\n\n===Growth===\nRegional sections were established in IFT as early as 1940 in northern California (San Francisco, [[Bakersfield]], [[Sacramento]]).<ref>[http://www.ift.org/sections/ncift/oldguard.htm Northern California IFT Section Chairs]</ref> The first IFT Award, the [[Nicholas Appert Award]] was established in 1942 by IFT's Chicago section with additional awards being established since then. For the first ten years, IFT officers were President, Vice-President, Secretary, and Treasurer. In 1949, IFT moved into offices in Chicago and created a permanent position of Executive Secretary to run daily organizational operations. Retired [[U.S. Army]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[Charles S. Lawrence]] was named the first Executive Secretary, a position he would hold until 1961 when he was replaced by [[Calvert L. Willey]]. During Willey's term as Executive Director (Executive Secretary 1961\u20131966), IFT would grow from 6,000 members in 1961 to 23,000 members in 1987.<ref>\"In Memoriam: Calvert L. Willey.\" ''Food Technology'' June 1994. pp. 20\u201321.</ref> Additionally, IFT Divisions were established in 1971 with the [[Refrigeration|Refrigerated]] and [[Frozen Foods]] Division being the first.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ift.org/divisions/food_eng/comm/april2006/IFT-FED%20Webletter%20May%202006.htm |title=Heldman, Dennis R. \"Proposed Changes in IFT Divisions.\" ''IFT-FED Webletter''. May 2006. Accessed October 7, 2006 |access-date=October 7, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701105854/http://www.ift.org/divisions/food_eng/comm/april2006/IFT-FED%20Webletter%20May%202006.htm |archive-date=July 1, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [http://www.iftsa.org/ IFT Student Division] was established in 1975, and was reorganized in 1984 to be the IFT Student Association with the chairperson serving as a member of the IFT Board of Directors.<ref>[http://www.iftsa.org/whoweare/history.php IFT Student Association history]</ref>\n\n===Today===\nThe governing body of IFT consists of a Board of Directors made up of the President, President-Elect, Immediate Past-President, Treasurer, Student Association President, Student Association Immediate Past President, IFT Foundation Chair, and Executive Vice President, along with twelve board members. IFT also communicates with the news media, using sixty scientists to discuss the scientific perspective on food issues.<ref>[http://www.ift.org/newsroom.aspx IFT-News Room]</ref> IFT is also active in the international level by its membership in the [[International Union of Food Science and Technology]], headquartered in [[Oakville, Ontario]], Canada.<ref>[http://www.iufost.org/home IUFoST links with IFT]</ref><ref>Heldman, D.R. \"IFT and International Food Science.\" ''Food Technology.'' November 2006: 11.</ref> Education has always been a focus of IFT, going as far back as 1941, with the desire to have uniform education standards in food technology.<ref name=\"HeldmanFoodScience\">Heldman, D. R. \"IFT and the Food Science Profession.\" ''Food Technology.'' October 2006. p. 11.</ref> Education standards for undergraduate students were approved by IFT in 1966 for food science and technology. These standards were revised and updated in 1977, 1992, 2001, and 2011. Today, IFT sits on the advisory council for the [[International Food Protection Training Institute]].\n\n===IFT Annual Meeting & Food Expo===\nIFT largest in-person gathering is IFT\u2019s Annual Meeting & Food Expo.<ref>http://www.am-fe.ift.org/</ref> This event, which offers more than 100 scientific and applied education sessions and an expo featuring 1,000+ exhibiting companies, regularly attracts 23,000 food professionals from more than 90 countries.\n\n===Certification===\nIFT offers the Certified Food Scientist (CFS) designation. The CFS is the only globally-recognized certification for food scientists, and has more than 1600 certificants in 55 countries. The CFS program is officially endorsed by the Australian Institute of Food Science Technology (AIFST) as well as the Canadian Institute of Food Science and Technology (CIFST). Earning the CFS consists of meeting certain academic and work experience requirements and passing an exam in the following content areas:\n* Product Development \n* Quality Assurance and Quality Control \n* Food Chemistry and Food Analysis \n* Regulatory \n* Food Microbiology \n* Food Safety \n* Food Engineering \n* Sensory Evaluation and Consumer Testing\n\nIt was designed to meet the International Standards Organization (ISO) 17024 standards for certification programs.\n\n===Global Food Traceability Center===\nIFT\u2019s Global Food Traceability Center (GFTC) is the global resource and authoritative voice on food traceability. Supported by its Founding Sponsors and guided by its Advisory Council, GFTC is designed to accelerate adoption and implementation of practical traceability solutions across the global [[food system]].\n\nThe Center works to deliver events, research, and support services that will help to increase understanding of food traceability across four business platforms:\n* Research\n* Protocols & Standards\n* Education & Training\n* Technology Transfer\n\n==Awards==\nAll awards except the Loncin prize have this reference<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://members.ift.org/NR/rdonlyres/A4E0668B-2F2C-4AFC-8F67-101350093BBE/0/AchievementAwardsNomination.doc |title=Achievement Awards Nomination (Word file) |access-date=October 5, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060302063935/http://members.ift.org/NR/rdonlyres/A4E0668B-2F2C-4AFC-8F67-101350093BBE/0/AchievementAwardsNomination.doc |archive-date=March 2, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> listed below.\n\n* [[Nicholas Appert Award]] (1942) \u2013 IFT's highest honor. Lifetime contributions to food technology.\n* [[Babcock-Hart Award]] (1948) \u2013 Significant contributions in food technology that resulted in [[public health]] improvements through some aspect of nutrition.\n* [[Bor S. Luh International Award]] (1956 \u2013 International Award from 1956 to 2004) \u2013 Individual member or institution that had outstanding efforts in one of the following in food technology: 1) international exchange of ideas, 2) better international understanding, and/or 3) practical successful technology transfer to an economically depressed area in a developed or developing nation.\n* [[Food Technology Industrial Achievement Award]] (1959) \u2013 Developing an outstanding food process or product that represents a significant advance in food technology or food production.\n* [[Samuel Cate Prescott Award]] (1964) \u2013 Outstanding ability of research in food technology. This is for researchers who are under 36 years of age or who are a maximum ten years after earning their highest academic degree whichever is later.\n* [[William V. Cruess Award]] (1970) \u2013 Excellence in teaching food science and technology. It is the only award that students can vote.\n* [[Carl R. Fellers Award]] (1984) \u2013 For IFT members who have brought honor and recognition to food science through achievements in areas other than education, research, development, and technology transfer.\n* [[Calvert L. Willey Award]] (1989) \u2013 For meritorious and imaginative service in IFT.\n* [[Stephen S. Chang Award for Lipid or Flavor Science]] (1993) \u2013 For contribution in [[lipid]] and [[flavor]] science.\n* [[IFT Industrial Scientist Award]] (1994) \u2013 For technical contributions that advances the food industry.\n* [[Marcel Loncin Research Prize]] (1994)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://members.ift.org/IFT/Awards/MarceLoncinResearchPrize |title=Marcel Loncin Research Prize |access-date=October 5, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002114011/http://members.ift.org/IFT/Awards/MarceLoncinResearchPrize/ |archive-date=October 2, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>- For basic research involving chemistry, physics, and food engineering applied to food research and food quality.\n* [[IFT Research & Development Award]] (1997) \u2013 For significant research and development contributions to better understanding within food science, food technology, and nutrition.\n* [[Elizabeth Fleming Stier Award]] (1997) \u2013 Humanitarian and unselfish dedication that results in significant contributions to the well-being in the food industry, academia, general public, or students.\n* [[Bernard L. Oser Award]] (2000) \u2013 For contributing to the scientific knowledge of food ingredient safety or in leadership in establishing food ingredient safety evaluation or regulation.\n* [[Myron Solberg Award]] (2004) \u2013 For providing leadership in establishing, successfully developing, and continuing a cooperative organization involving [[academia]], government, and industry.\n* Sensory and Consumer Sciences Achievement Award (2014) \u2013To recognize excellence within the sensory and consumer sciences field.\n* Gilbert A. Leveille Award and Lectureship (2014) \u2013 Recognizes outstanding research and/or public service at the interface between the disciplines of nutrition and food science, over a period of five years or more, which has contributed to improved health and well-being.\n* WK Kellogg International Food Security Award (2012) \u2013 To honor an IFT member working in academics, research institutes or the government, regardless of geographic origin, whose outstanding efforts result in one or more of the following: (1) Enabling and increasing access to nutritious food in non-industrialized countries; (2) Developing emerging technologies and/or research that addresses non-industrialized countries food needs, food safety, and food security; and/or (3) Contributing toward the technological development in one or more local food industries to help foster economic development in non-industrialized countries.\n\n==Divisions==\nThese are divisions of interest by the IFT Members<ref>[http://www.ift.org/community/divisions.aspx IFT Divisions]</ref>\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* Aquatic Food Products \u2013 seafood\n* [[Biotechnology]]\n* [[Carbohydrate]]\n* Dairy Foods \u2013 [[dairy products]]\n* Education\n* Extension and Outreach\n* [[Food Chemistry]]\n* [[Food Engineering]]\n* [[Food politics|Food Law]] and Regulations \u2013 legal aspects in food processing and technology\n* [[Food Microbiology]]\n* [[Food Packaging]]\n* [[Foodservice]] \u2013 restaurants.\n* Fruit & Vegetable Products\n* [http://www.iftsa.org IFT Student Association]\n* International\n* Marketing & Management\n* Muscle Foods \u2013 meat, poultry, and seafood\n* Nonthermal Processing \u2013 [[food processing]] through using alternative lethal agents such as high pressure, electric field, UV, ultrasound and cold plasma\n* [[Nutraceuticals]] & Functional Foods \u2013 Combining nutrition and medicine for healthy living\n* Nutrition\n* [[Product Development]] \u2013 Developing foods from the laboratory to the general public\n* [[Quality Assurance]] \u2013 [[food quality]]\n* Refrigerated and Frozen Foods \u2013 foods that are processed through [[refrigeration]] and [[freezing]]\n* [[Sensory and Consumer Sciences]]\n* [[Toxicology]] and Safety Evaluation \u2013 [[food allergy]] mainly\n{{colend}}\n\n==Sections==\nThese are usually cities, states, and regions. If a region is mentioned, a city in that region is mentioned which include areas surrounded by the city.<ref>[http://www.ift.org/community/sections.aspx IFT Sections]</ref>\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* AK-SAR-BEN \u2013 [[Nebraska]]\n* Alamo \u2013 [[San Antonio]], Texas\n* Bluegrass \u2013 [[Kentucky]]\n* Bonneville \u2013 [[Utah]]\n* British \u2013 Great Britain\n* [[British Columbia]] \u2013 Canadian province\n* Cactus \u2013 [[Arizona]]\n* Central [[New Jersey]] \u2013 subsection of New York Section\n* Central Valley \u2013 subsection of Northern California section\n* Chicago\n* Dogwood \u2013 [[North Carolina]]\n* Florida\n* Great Lakes \u2013 [[Michigan]]\n* Great Plains \u2013 [[South Dakota]], subsection of Minnesota section\n* Hawaii\n* [[Indiana]]\n* Intermountain \u2013 [[Idaho]]\n* [[Iowa]]\n* Japan\n* Kansas City \u2013 [[Kansas]] and western [[Missouri]]\n* Keystone \u2013 [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]\n* Lake Erie \u2013 [[Cleveland]], Ohio\n* Lewis & Clark\n* Long Island \u2013 [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]] and [[Queens]], New York\n* Longhorn \u2013 [[Dallas]], Texas\n* [[Louisiana]] Gulf Coast \u2013 New Orleans, Louisiana\n* Magnolia \u2013 [[Mississippi]]\n* [[Maryland]] \u2013 includes [[Delaware]] and [[West Virginia]]\n* Mid-South \u2013 [[Memphis, Tennessee]] and eastern [[Arkansas]]\n* [[Minnesota]]\n* New York \u2013 New York City boroughs of [[Manhattan]], [[Staten Island]], and [[Bronx]], and parts of northern [[New Jersey]].\n* Northeast \u2013 [[Maine]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New Hampshire]], [[Rhode Island]], and [[Vermont]]\n* Northern California \u2013 San Francisco, Sacramento, Bakersfield\n* Northwest [[Ohio]] \u2013 [[Toledo, Ohio]]\n* Nutmeg \u2013 [[Connecticut]]\n* Ohio Valley \u2013 [[Cincinnati]] and [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n* [[Oklahoma]]\n* [[Oregon]]\n* Ozark \u2013 Western Arkansas and southwest Missouri\n* [[Philadelphia]] \u2013 Includes eastern Pennsylvania\n* [[Pittsburgh]] \u2013 Includes western Pennsylvania\n* Puget Sound \u2013 [[Seattle]], Washington and [[Alaska]]\n* Rocky Mountain \u2013 [[Colorado]] and [[University of Wyoming]]\n* San Joaquin\u2013 Bakersfield, Fresno, California\n* South Eastern \u2013 [[Alabama]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], and [[South Carolina]] (Dixie: 1950\u20132007)\n* South Florida \u2013 Miami, Florida\n* Southern California \u2013 Los Angeles and San Diego\n* [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] \u2013 includes southern [[Illinois]] and eastern Missouri\n* Volunteer \u2013 All of [[Tennessee]] except Memphis\n* Washington, D.C. \u2013 includes [[Virginia]]\n* Western New York\n* [[Wisconsin]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Executive vice presidents==\nBetween IFT's founding in 1939 and 1949, the institute had elected a secretary and treasurer that kept up with the daily operations of the institute. By 1949, the membership had reached 3,000 and it was decided to create an Executive Secretary position and establish national office in Chicago. Since then, the position's name has changed twice to its current name. There have been six Executive Vice Presidents<ref>[http://www.ift.org/Newsroom/News-Releases/2014/March/07/New-EVP.aspx]</ref> shown below:\n\n*[[Charles S. Lawrence]]: 1949\u201361\n*[[Calvert L. Willey]]: 1961\u201387\n*[[Howard W. Mattson]]: 1987\u201391\n*[[Daniel E. Weber]]: 1991\u20132003\n*[[Barbara Byrd Keenan]]: 2003\u20132013\n*[[Christie Tarantino, FASAE, CAE]]: 2014\u2013Present\n\n==Member grades==\nThere are four member grades within IFT:<ref>[http://www.ift.org/cms/?pid=1000332 IFT Member Grades]</ref>\n\n*Student member \u2013 A full-time student working on an [[Associate of Science]] degree or higher in food science, food technology, or a related field. All applications must be endorsed by a faculty member.\n*Member \u2013 A person active in the food industry who shows interest in supporting the Institute's objective.\n*Professional Member \u2013 An IFT member who has five years of experience within food science or technology whether it is academic, government, or industrial. A member with a [[Master of Science]] degree can earn one year of experience while member with a [[Doctorate of Philosophy]] degree can earn three years of experience to assist in qualification.\n*Emeritus Member \u2013 Any retired Member or Professional Member who has been an IFT Member for a minimum of twenty years.\n\n==Presidents==\n \n2019-2020       Pam Coleman\n\n2018-2019       Michelle Perchonok\n\n2017-2018       Cindy Steward   \n\n2016-2017       John Coupland\n\n2015-2016 \tColin Dennis\n\n2014-2015 \tMary Ellen Camire\n\n2013-2014 \tJanet Collins\n\n2012-2013 \tJohn Ruff\n\n2011-2012 \tRoger A. Clemens\n\n2010-2011 \tRobert B Gravani\n\n2009-2010 \tMarianne Gillette\n\n2008-2009 \tSheri Schellhaass\n\n2007-2008 \tJohn Floros\n\n2006-2007 \tDennis Heldman\n\n2005-2006 \tMargaret Lawson\n\n2004-2005 \tHerbert Stone\n\n2003-2004 \tC. Ann Hollingsworth*\n\n2002-2003 \tMark R. McClellan\n\n2001-2002 \tPhilip Nelson\n\n2000-2001 \tMary K. Schmidl\n\n1999-2000 \tCharles H. Manley\n\n1998-1999 \tBruce H. Stillings\n\n1997-1998 \tMary K. Wagner\n\n1996-1997 \tRobert E. Smith\n\n1995-1996 \tFrank F. Busta\n\n1994-1995 \tRoy G. Arnold\n\n1993-1994 \tAl S. Clausi\n\n1992-1993 \tDavid R. Lineback\n\n1991-1992 \tJohn H. Litchfield\n\n1990-1