*\n\n1948-1949 \tH.C. Diehl*\n\n1947-1948 \tGeorge J. Hucker*\n\n1946-1947 \tEllery H. Harvey*\n\n1945-1946 \tFred W. Tanner*\n\n1944-1945 \tFred C. Blanck*\n\n1943-1944 \tWilliam V. Cruess*\n\n1942-1943 \tRoy C. Newton*\n\n1941-1942 \tLaurence B. Burton*\n\n1939-1941 \tSamuel Cate. Prescott*\n\n\n* = Deceased<ref>http://www.ift.org/about-us/our-leadership/past-presidents.aspx</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nThe Institute also has many publications that are both in print and online<ref name=\"IFT Publications\">[http://www.ift.org/IFT/Pubs IFT Publications]</ref> that are shown below:\n\n* ''[[Food Technology (magazine)|Food Technology]]'' (1947) \u2013 IFT's monthly magazine available to all members. Besides the monthly columns dealing with [[food processing]], [[food packaging]], [[ingredients]], food safety and quality, [[nutraceuticals]], food, medicine & health, culinary, and consumer trends, it also focuses on in-depth issues such as [[biotechnology]], [[food safety]], and nutrition.<ref>[http://www.ift.org/food-technology.aspx ''Food Technology'' magazine]</ref>\n* ''[[Journal of Food Science]]'' or '''''JFS''''' (Founded in 1936 as ''[[Food Research]]'') \u2013 IFT's premier [[scientific journal]] dealing with all [[peer-reviewed]] aspects of [[food science]] ([[food chemistry]], [[food microbiology]], [[food engineering]], toxicology, nanoscale materials, nutrition, and [[sensory evaluation]]. It annually publishes over 400 papers and 2,500 pages with authors from 90 countries and readers from 50 countries internationally. The [[Library of Congress]] in 2004 put ''JFS'' as one of only 300 journals as a high priority ... ([[ISSN]]).<ref>[http://www.ift.org/IFT/Pubs/JournalofFoodSci ''Journal of Food Science'']</ref>\n\nBoth ''Food Technology'' and the ''Journal of Food Science'' can be accessed in print or online. Other publications are shown below:\n\n* ''[[The Journal of Food Science Education]]'' or '''''JSFE''''' (2002 \u2013 Online only) \u2013 This quarterly journal deals with innovations, techniques, and methods to improve education in food science and technology.<ref>[http://www.ift.org/IFT/Pubs/JFSE ''The Journal of Food Science Education'']</ref>\n* ''[[Comprehensive Reviews in Food Science and Food Safety]]'' (2002 \u2013 Online only) \u2013 This journal, published bimonthly, deals with a broad review of a narrowly defined topic relating to food science and technology, including [[physiology]], economics, history, nutrition, microbiology, engineering, processing, and [[genetics]]. All aspects of these reviews are studied, including strengths, weaknesses, and research differences in order to present insightful investigation, including interpretation, summary, and conclusion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://members.ift.org/IFT/Pubs/CRFSFS |title=''Comprehensive Reviews in Food Science and Food Safety'' |access-date=October 7, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002112111/http://members.ift.org/IFT/Pubs/CRFSFS/ |archive-date=October 2, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''IFT Weekly Newsletter'' \u2013 A weekly e-mail newsletter sent out every Wednesday about issues within the food industry, including food companies, food research, food regulations, and IFT itself.<ref name=\"IFTNewsletters\">[http://www.ift.org/IFT/Pubs/Newsletters IFT Newsletters]</ref>\n* ''Nutraceutical Newsletter'' \u2013 An e-mail newsletter similar to the ''IFT Weekly Newsletter'' though it deals specifically with nutraceuticals and functional foods.<ref name=\"IFTNewsletters\"/>\n* IFT Books \u2013 The Institute has four book publishers that offer membership discounts, including IFT Press (a partnership with [[Wiley-Blackwell]]), Grey House Publishing, [[DESteck Publications]], and Taylor and Francis, on food science and technology.<ref name=\"IFTBooks\">[http://www.ift.org/IFT/Pubs/Books Books]</ref>\n* Three annual buyers guides are also published: ''Food Technology Buyer's Guide'', ''Nutraceutical Buyer's Guide'', and ''Annual Guide to Food Industry Services''. These are usually published as a supplement to ''Food Technology'' magazine.<ref name=\"IFTBooks\"/>\nIn 2016 they initiated and funded the documentary [[Food Evolution]] by [[Scott Hamilton Kennedy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Wanucha, Genevieve. \"Two Happy Clams: The Friendship that Forged Food Science.\" ''Food Technology''. November 2009. p.&nbsp;69.\n\n==Concerns==\nOne constant that IFT has concern with is [[food safety]], mainly with [[pathogens]] in food (see [[food microbiology]]) and how to counter these harmful bacteria. The global trade of food is also concerned with food safety and food security, specifically with ingredient availability and consumer tastes worldwide. Food traceability, food fraud, obesity, and how science and technology will help feed the world\u2019s projected 9 billion-plus people in 2050 have all become main issues for IFT.\n\n{{Food science}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Institute Of Food Technologists}}\n[[Category:Agricultural organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Food technology organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1939]]\n[[Category:Food safety organizations]]\n[[Category:1939 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Sadads", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkfood systemusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_of_Food_Technologists"}
{"title_page": "Round Hill (Greene County, New York)", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Round Hill\n| photo = \n| photo_caption = \n| elevation = {{convert|2589|ft}}\n| elevation_ref = \n| listing = \n| location = WSW of [[Maplecrest, New York|Maplecrest]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| range =\n| coordinates = {{coord|42.2709193|-74.2137531|type:mountain_region:US-NY_scale:100000_source:GNIS|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref =<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis\n  | id = 962965\n  | name = Round Hill\n  | accessdate = 2018-04-05 }}</ref>\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] ''Hensonville''\n| map = New York Adirondack Park#USA\n| map_caption = Location of Round Hill within New York\n| type = \n| age = \n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Round Hill''' is a [[mountain]] in [[Greene County, New York]]. It is located in the [[Catskill Mountains]] west-southwest of [[Maplecrest, New York|Maplecrest]]. [[Van Loan Hill]] is located east, and [[East Jewett Range]] is located south of Round Hill.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mountains of New York}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Greene County, New York]]\n[[Category:Mountains of New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{GreeneCountyNY-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Round Hill\n| photo = \n| photo_caption = \n| elevation = {{convert|2589|ft}}\n| elevation_ref = \n| listing = \n| location = WSW of [[Maplecrest, New York|Maplecrest]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| range =\n| coordinates = {{coord|42.2709193|-74.2137531|type:mountain_region:US-NY_scale:100000_source:GNIS|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref =<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis\n  | id = 962965\n  | name = Round Hill\n  | accessdate = 2018-04-05 }}</ref>\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] ''Hensonville''\n| map = New York#USA Adirondack Park#USA\n| map_caption = Location of Round Hill within New York\n| type = \n| age = \n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Round Hill''' is a [[mountain]] in [[Greene County, New York]]. It is located in the [[Catskill Mountains]] west-southwest of [[Maplecrest, New York|Maplecrest]]. [[Van Loan Hill]] is located east, and [[East Jewett Range]] is located south of Round Hill.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mountains of New York}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Greene County, New York]]\n[[Category:Mountains of New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{GreeneCountyNY-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fix map error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Round_Hill_(Greene_County,_New_York)"}
{"title_page": "Nomads of India", "text_new": "{{short description|Nomadic communities in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n[[Nomads]] are known as a group of communities who travel from place to place for their livelihood. Some are salt traders, [[fortune-teller]]s, [[conjurers]], [[ayurvedic]] healers, [[jugglers]], [[Acrobatics|acrobats]], actors, [[Storytelling|story teller]]s, [[snake charmers]], animal doctors, [[tattooist]]s, [[Millstone|grindstone]] makers, or [[basketmaker]]s. Some [[anthropologist]]s have identified about 8 nomadic groups in [[India]], numbering perhaps 1 million people\u2014around 1.2 percent of the country's billion-plus population.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Nomads in India : proceedings of the National Seminar / edited by P.K. Misra, K.C. Malhotra</ref>{{full}} [[Aparna Rao]] and Michael Casimir estimated that nomads make up around 7% of the population of India.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Nomadic Peoples |volume=8 |issue=2, ''Whither South Asian Pastoralism?'' |page=274 |year=2004 |publisher=White Horse Press |editor-first=Bahram |editor-last=Tavakolian |accessdate=April 25, 2020 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43123738?seq=1 |quote=In fact Rao and Casimir point out that the largest numbers of nomads in the world are not to be found in the Middle East and Africa, where most past studies have directed our attention, but in South Asia where they contribute 7 percent of India's huge population (2003: 1).}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Participatory Citizenship: Identity, Exclusion, Inclusion |first1=Ranjita |last1=Mohanty |first2=Rajesh |last2=Tandon |authorlink2=Rajesh Tandon |publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]] |place=India |url=https://books.google.ru/books?id=qoFjDwAAQBAJ&q=India+nomadic+7+per+cent |pages=110-111 |year=2006 |ISBN=978-9352805457 |quote=The nomadic population in the South Asia is the largest in the world. In India, nomadic communities form nearly 7 per cent of population and consists of about 500 different communities of mobile herders, foragers and traditional peripatetics (Rao and Casimir 2003 :1).}}</ref>\n\nThe nomadic communities in India can be broadly divided into three groups [[Hunter-gatherer|hunter gatherers]], [[pastoral]]ists and the [[Nomad#Peripatetic minorities|peripatetic]] or non-food producing groups. Among these, peripatetic nomads are the most neglected and discriminated social group in India.<ref>Customary strangers : new perspectives on peripatetic peoples in the Middle East, Africa, and Asia / edited by Joseph C. Berland and Aparna Rao</ref> They have lost their livelihood because of drastic changes in transport, industries, production, entertainment and distribution systems. They find pastures for their herders\n\n== Historic development ==\n\nNomadic tribes have always been a source of suspicion to [[Sedentism|sedentary]] people. In the colonial period, the British normalized a set of notions about such groups that echoed European ideas about the [[Romani people|gypsies]], whose [[History of the Romani people|origins are in the Indian subcontinent]]. They listed such groups that posed a \u2018threat\u2019 to settled society and introduced a legislative measure, the [[Criminal Tribes Act]] (CTA) in 1871 and as a result of which nearly 200 such communities stood \u2018notified\u2019 as criminal.\n\nThe Targalas or Nayaks have been [[Itinerant groups in Europe|itinerant]] drama troupes in [[Gujarat]] who moved from village to village to perform \u2018[[Bhavai]]\u2019, a [[folk dance]] theatre form. These performers too carry the stigma of criminality. There are numerous folk tales of \u2018the skillful thefts\u2019 allegedly committed by Bhavai troupe members. And if a burglary had taken place in a village where Bhavai had been performed, members of the troupe would be arrested and interrogated. The itinerant Bhavai players have always been expected to report their entry, stay and exit to the village headman.\n\nThe folk dance drama of [[Bhavai]] probably originated in the then Anart Pradesh (now North Gujarat). It then spread over other parts of Gujarat, [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], [[Kutch]] and [[Marvad]] (now [[Rajasthan]]). It has been a popular form of entertainment among the rural and the townsfolk from the 14th century through to the 19th century in the North-west region of India. Although its origin are in the worship of the Mother Goddess, [[Bhavani]], it has gathered secular elements with the passage of time and come to embrace the whole range of human emotions of the rural community. It is to Gujarat what [[Yakshagana]] is to [[Karnataka]], [[Nautanki]] to [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Tamasha]] and [[Lalit (raga)|Lalit]] to [[Maharashtra]] - a veritable folk dance drama.\n\nThe performing Targalas are believed to be the descendants of the poet [[Asait Thakar]] of [[Unjha]] who lived in the 14th century. As the legend goes, Asait was an Audichya Brahmin of [[Unjha]] in North Gujarat. His host Hemala Patel\u2019s daughter Ganga was kidnapped by a Rawal Ratan Singh, Sardar Jahan Roz. Hemala Patel urged Asait Thakar to use his artistic skills to help liberate his daughter from the Sardar. Asait told the Sardar, after pleasing him with his performance and songs that he should liberate the girl, who he claimed was his.\n\nIndian distinguished  from other nomads in India in that they breed animals and this distinguishes them from other groups that which make a living by combining with other itinerant professions such as blacksmithing by [[Gadia Lohar]], or selling salt by the [[Lambadi]].  These pastoral groups are concentrated in certain regions such as the [[semi-arid]] and arid [[Thar Desert|Thar]] desert region and the neighbouring [[salt marsh]]es of [[Kutch]] along the [[Indo-Pakistan border]], the [[alpine climate|alpine]] and [[sub-alpine]] zones above 3200 metres in the [[Himalayas]] forming the states of [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[Himachal Pradesh]] and [[Uttarakhand]].<ref name=\"dfid.gov.uk\">http://www.dfid.gov.uk/r4d/PDF/outputs/ZC0181b.pdf</ref>\n\nTypes of livestock kept in mobile pastoral systems include buffaloes, sheep, goats, camels, cattle, donkeys, and [[yaks]] among others. Unlike in the [[Middle East]], where pastoralist are organized in tribes occupying distinct areas, in India pastoralist are integrated in the [[caste]] system, representing [[endogamous group|endogamous]] social units specialising in animal husbandry.<ref name=\"dfid.gov.uk\"/>\n\nIn western India in the [[Kutch]] region, there are a groups of pastoral nomads known as the [[Maldhari]]. The word ''Maldhari'' means in the local [[Kutchi language]] means an \"owner of animal stock\".<ref name=\"BI \">\n{{citation\n|url= http://www.biodiversityofindia.org/index.php?title=Maldhari_tribe_and_their_clash_with_lion_conservation \n|title=Maldhari tribe and their clash with lion conservation \n|work=on Biodiversity of India wiki\n|publisher=\n|date=2011-11-25\n|accessdate=2012-02-23\n}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ List of major pastoral nomadic communities in India<ref name=\"dfid.gov.uk\"/>\n|-\n! Pastoral Group  !!  State and location!! Ethnic Identity || Species\n|-\n| '''  [[Bakarwal]] '''   ||   '''   [[Jammu and Kashmir]] '''  || ||  mainly goats\n|-\n| '''  [[Bharwad]]         '''   ||       '''   [[Gujarat]] '''   ||   [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] speaking Hindu group            || Motabhai raise sheep and goat, and Nanabhai are cattle breeders\n|-\n|   ''' [[Uttarakhand Bhotiya|Bhotia]]'''   ||       ''' [[Uttarakhand]], upper regions of [[Garhwal division|Garhwal]] and [[Kumaon division|Kumaon]]          '''   ||   Mainly Hindu, some Buddhist, speak [[Central Pahari languages|Pahari]]  || Sheep, Goats and cattle\n|-\n| '''[[Bhutia]]'''   ||    ''' [[North Sikkim district|North district]] of [[Sikkim]]    '''   ||  [[Buddhist]], speaking [[Tibetan languages|Tibetan dialects]]  ||  sheep, goats and cattle   \n|-\n|   ''' [[Changpa]